<HTML> <HEAD>

<TITLE>Air Pollution and Health</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>



<IMG SRC="images/folio.gif" ALT="GreenBeat!" ALIGN=top WIDTH=456 HEIGHT=72><BR>
<P>



<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="images/scrunch.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="ACHOO!" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=72 BORDER=1><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+3><B>Air Pollution and Health
</B></FONT><br><FONT SIZE=+1><I>by Dan Horowitz</I></FONT>

</CENTER>


&nbsp;<BR>

<font size=+1><B>What is Air Pollution?</B><P>

Pollution is by definition to make dirty, impure, or to corrupt.  When we
consider air pollution, we are considering the adulteration of the air, the air
we must breathe to stay alive.  At certain levels of air pollution, we die. 
Before those fatal levels, we become sick.  Children, the elderly, and those with
respiratory problems such as asthma are more susceptible to air pollution than
the general public because these people have decreased lung ability.  Air
pollution in even small quantities exacerbates their problems making it more
difficult for them to breathe.  At slightly higher levels of air pollution, even
the healthiest lungs among us are affected.<P>

<B>Why Worry?</B><P>

An EPA electronic pamphlet introduces the topic:<p>

<CITE>Why should you be concerned about air pollution?<p>

Air pollution can make you sick. It can cause burning eyes and nose and an itchy,
irritated throat, as well as trouble in breathing. Some chemicals found in
polluted air cause cancer, birth defects, brain and nerve damage and long-term
injury to the lungs and breathing passages. Some air pollutants are so dangerous
that accidental releases can cause serious injury or even death.<p>

Air pollution can damage the environment. Trees, lakes and animals have been
harmed by air pollution. Air pollutants have thinned the protective ozone layer
above the Earth; this loss of ozone could cause changes in the environment as
well as more skin cancer and cataracts (eye damage) in people.<P>

Air pollution can damage property. It can dirty buildings and other structures.
Some common pollutants eat away stone, damaging buildings, monuments and statues.<P>

Air pollution can cause haze, reducing visibility in national parks and sometime
interfering with aviation.<P></CITE>

<B>Pollution and Lungs</B><P>

Intuitively, the majority of health-related problems that result from air
pollution occur in the lungs.  As the organs of breathing, our lungs are our
interface with the air.  When we breathe, we are providing our bodies with
oxygen.  Lack of oxygen produces noticeable effects.  At higher altitudes, people
become dizzy and faint because the amount of oxygen in the air is smaller.  When
the air is polluted, not only is there less oxygen in the air, which causes
breathing difficulties, but therh levels of air pollution and increased risk of
death (by 15-17%) </font><font size =-1><A HREF="http://www.hsph.harvard.edu/News/950310.html">Harvard
School of Public Health Study.</A><P></font>

<font size=+1><B>Air Pollution and Children</B><P>

For many reasons children are especially prone to the dangers of high ozone
levels.  Their lungs have narrower airways which increases chances of
obstruction.  Children have higher ventilation rates which increase the volume of
air they inhale.  They spend more time outdoors, and engage in more vigorous
physical activity, especially during the summer months, when ozone levels are
already increased.  During exercise, children and adults breathe with both their
noses and mouths, which bypasses the filters of the sinus pathway.<P>

<B>Forms of Air Pollution</B><P>

The major forms of air pollution, as established by the EPA, are ozone, sulfur
dioxide, nitrogen dioxide, carbon monoxide, repirable particulate matter, and
lead.  National Ambient Air Quality Standards are set for each of these six
pollutants and are monitored by the Texas Natural Resource Conservation
Commission (TNRCC) through a network statewide affiliates.<P>

The EPA has designated four areas in Texas that violate the national ozone
standard (120 parts per billion): Houston-Galvestion-Brazoria, Beaumont-Port
Arthur, Dallas-Fort Worth, and El Paso.  In these areas, people should be
especially aware of the adverse health effects of ozone and should alter their
behavior to compensate.  Jennifer Bartkowski of the American Lung Association
said, The number of of people who go into emergency rooms with respiratory
problems increases on days of high ozone.  She said the exact numbers are hard
to determine, but there is a definite correlation.  She reaffirmed that high
ozone levels are especially dangerous for children, the elderly, and others with
existing cardiopulminary problems.<P>


<B>Quantity of Pollutants</B><P>

Air pollution depends upon quantity.  The poisons in the dose, and with air
pollutants the doses are small.  Because the atmosphere is so big, we have in the
past been misled into thinking that whatever we put into the air will dissipate. 
In the 1800s the problem of air pollution concentrated at ground level was
recognized and smokestacks were created to vent our pollutants higher into the
sky.  The pollution was evident as black noxious clouds, its deleterious effects
were prevalent, so it was shot up and away from ourselves, but the problem didn't
end there.  Pollution depends heavily on weather conditions.  Ozone is present in
higher quantities during the summer, and low pressure systems keep air pollution
closer to the ground and less able to disperse.<P>

<B>Smog</B><P>

A familiar and still poignant example of urban air pollution is smog, like the
smog that is associated with the haze around Los Angeles.  Smog is a combination
of chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs) and ozone (O3), which is created in atmospheric
reactions with nitrogen oxides (NO).  The visibility of smog makes it an easier
target than some forms of air pollution.  By themselves, invisible CFCs deplete
the upper atmosphere ozone layer, which is the same type of ozone that at ground
level poses other health risks.  Depleting the upper atmosphere ozone layer
allows more ultraviolet radiation to penetrate the atmosphere, increasing the
risk of skin cancer.<P>

During Dec.  5-8, 1952, a killer smog was responsible for an estimated
3,500-4,000 deaths in London.  In 1948, a stagnant air mass sent over 10 percent
of the population of Donora, Pa., to hospitals[Ibid].<P>

<B>Reducing Air Pollution</B><P>

There are many ways to decrease the amount of pollutants in the air, but
individually, the easiest ways are related to use of automobiles.  The
Environmental Protection Agency offers many suggestions in a pamphlet called
"Your Car and the Environment."  By reducing the amount of time we spend in our
cars, and increasing the number of people with which we share rides, pollutants
from engine emissions can be reduced.  The EPA suggests carpooling, bicycling to
work, and using mass transit busses and trains.  Additionally, the EPA suggests
ways to increase fuel efficiency, thereby burning less fuel and emitte are also
harmful gases and pariculate matter in the air that cause more breathing
difficulties and also can damage our lungs directly.<P>

An American Lung Association Pamphlet pamphlet states that lung disease claims
more than 300,000 lives in America every year and is the third-leading cause of
death in the United States.  Air pollution contributes to lung disease, including
respiratory tract infections, asthma, and lung cancer.  Pollutants cause the
bronchi, the tubes between the lungs esophogus,  to constrict, thereby reducing
the amoung of oxygen that we can breathe into our lungs.  Particulate matter, for
example, can also lodge in our lungs, ripping tissues and amassing
carcinogenically.  Studies show high correlations between incidence of lung
cancer and areas of high air pollution.  Even if we suffer no perceived immediate
problems in breathing, air pollution still may be shortening our lives.  A 1995
Harvard study of over half-a-million people in 151 U.S. cities found positive
correlation between higing less pollution.  Combine trips, keep tires properly
inflated, keep car filters and catalytic converters clean, accelerate gradually,
and have the emissions system inspected regularly are all suggestions offered by
the EPA.<P>

Conserving electricity at home and work also helps to reduce air pollution. 
Electricity is widely generated by coal-fired plants which emit air pollution. 
By conserving electricity, the demand for coal to be burned is lessened as a
result.  Similarly, increasing reliance on sustainable energy sources (such as
the sun and wind) decreases reliance on polluting energy sources, almost
exclusively from oil- and coal-derived hydrocarbon fuels.<P>

In the meantime, as we continue trying to reduce air pollution, it is important
to consider levels of air pollution when spending time outdoors, especially when
engaging in strenuous activity.<P>





