<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> A Burning Issue
</TITLE>
</HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR= #FFFFFF>
 <IMG SRC="images/folio.gif" ALT = "Greenbeat!" ALIGN = top WIDTH = 456 HEIGHT = 72><BR><P>

<CENTER>


<FONT SIZE = +3><B>A Burning Issue:</B></FONT SIZE><BR>
<FONT SIZE = +2>Should We "Recycle" Tires as Fuel or New Products?</FONT SIZE><BR>
<FONT SIZE = +1><I>by Daniel Pace</I></FONT SIZE>

</CENTER>

<BR>
<FONT SIZE= +1>
<IMG SRC="images/tires.gif" ALIGN="right" WIDTH="141" HEIGHT="100" ALT="[Stack of Tires]">
Everything is bigger
and better in Texas.  This has long been a point of pride with Texans. 
Unfortunately, it relates to more than Dooley trucks and Stetson hats; it also
holds true for smog, pollution and levels of dangerous toxins.  <P>

Texas currently
holds the title of second most polluted state in the Union.  Yet recently, a number of cement kilns have received permits to power the
cement-making process with TDF, or "tire derived fuel."  Tires are burned as a fuel source, and many call this process "recycling."<P>

Cement kilns around the country using TDF claim
that tires burn cleaner and safer than coal.  They like to call it
"recycling" because they are reclaiming the energy value of the tire without
causing any harm to the environment.  However, the foundation of  this claim lies
in a test done by the EPA in 1991 which did not look for emissions beyond those
expected from coal.  Tires and coal are two entirely different substances; in
fact, it is impossible to tell what a specific tire contains because many
companies use different recipes in manufacturing them.  <P>

Statewide rules require commercial incinerators to employ advanced technology to
combat toxic emissions.  Cement kilns, on the other hand, are not equipped with
the more advanced technology, including scrubbers in the stack to prevent
build-up, dual incinerators for more efficient destruction, and constant
monitoring of the stack output which the state requires for commercial
incinerators.  Nor are cement kilns required to adhere to air quality laws that
incinerators must follow; their permitted emission rates are much higher.<P>

The truth is, burning
tires emits hundreds of toxic compounds into the air, some of the worst of which
- dioxins, furans, PCBs - are known to cause cancer as well as major reproductive
and immunological problems, even if present in very small amounts.  One stack
test at a kiln burning 30% TDF found major increases in a number of pollutants as
compared to 100% coal.  These include a 1432% increase in dioxins, 2230% increase
in furans, 388% increase in lead, the list goes on and is quite shocking.  The
heavy metals, such as lead, chromium, nickel, and cadmium tend to bind with the
particulate matter that is inevitable at a cement kiln.  When absorbed by the
lungs, the metals dissolve into soluble salts which can easily penetrate the
brain.  Exposure can also lead to respiratory irritation and asthma, two ailments
found increasingly in communities with cement kilns. <P>

 Americans discard 240 million tires every year, leaving us with stacks upon
stacks of tires.  The State of Texas assesses a $2 fee attached to the price of
all new tires, with the intention that the money be used to develop uses for
scrap tires.  Instead of encouraging entrepreneurs to find new and safe uses, the
State of Texas gives cement kilns 80 cents per tire to burn them, and calls it
recycling.  This eliminates a large portion of the budget for safe, effective
uses and pits cement kilns against upstart companies with other alternatives.  <P>

Granted, used tires are becoming a major problem, but incineration
is not the answer.  The Scrap Tire Management Council has developed many viable
alternatives.  Perhaps the most creative is in artificial reefs.  Using up to 2
million tires, artificial reefs can be created to provide habitat to fish.  With
their shock absorption value, tires also make excellent breakwaters to reduce
impact erosion on the shoreline.  <P>

On land, materials from shredded tires can be
used in paving road surface.  Rubber modified asphalt concrete (RUMAC) lasts two
to three times longer than conventional asphalt.  The list of products that can
be made from tires is actually quite long:  mats, flooring, tennis shoe soles,
dock bumpers, truck bed liners, even houses have been made with old tires. 
Perhaps the best alternative is keeping the tires out of the waste stream
entirely by retreading.  At least 38 million tires in use now could benefit from
retreading, adding years to the life of the tire.<P>

Incineration is the
worst means of destroying any form of waste, especially tires.  The pollution
that results puts entire communities at risk, children in particular.  Newborn
and young children are the most susceptible to the adverse effects of pollution. 
Given the numerous and useful alternatives, the millions of tires stacked around
Texas need to become valuable products, not toxic pollution.<P>


<FONT SIZE=1>
<CENTER>
