<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Evolution of the Movement</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>



<IMG SRC="images/folio.gif" ALT="GreenBeat!" ALIGN=top WIDTH=456 HEIGHT=72><BR>
<P>



<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3>Profile: Sue Johnson</FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>Evolution of the Environmental Movement</FONT><P>
by Mindy Jackson<BR> 
</CENTER>
<P>


<IMG SRC="images/sue.jpg" ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=126 HEIGHT=216 ALT="SUE JOHNSON" BORDER=1>

<font size=+1>
"I'm not an original tree hugger, although I love trees now and occassionally
speak to them," Sue Johnson says as she sips her iced coffee.<P>

"I've always been a hiker, camper, rock collector. And I like to garden," she
adds. "I've always had some tie to nature, but most of my life I did not consider
myself an environmentalist."<P>

The assertion surprises me, coming from one of Central Texas' most respected and
active environmental advocates.  Board chair of Ecology Action, elected board
member of the Barton Springs/Edwards Aquifer Conservation District, and
co-founder of the Environmental Sociology Section of the American Sociological
Association, Sue's resume reads like a who's-who listing of outstanding
environmentalists.<P>

Her thoughtful expression reflects back to me as she stares out the cafe window.
"I want to resist the title environmentalist because what I feel I'm about is
more than just environmentalism."<P>

Ecology Action is coordinating Austin's Earth Day 1996 celebration, and with her
close ties to some two dozen other environmental organizations in Austin, Sue
seemed like the perfect interview for GreenBeat!'s Earth Day cover story.<P>

She has a reputation as a solution-finder, win-win-moderator, and naysayer to the
word "impossible." I wanted to know her opinions on the present condition and
future of the environmental movement.<P>

<IMG SRC="images/quote.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=257 HEIGHT=78 ALT="quote">


"I think environmentalists these days have a kind of reactionary reputation. I
don't want that. They're seen as somehow obstructionists and negative," Sue
frowns, pauses for a moment then brightens. "Nature is so positive! It (present
environmentalism) seems the antithesis. Nature is life and positivism and
ever-changing movement."<P>

Bringing life, positivism and ever-changing movement to Austin's environmental
politics was Sue's mission when she co-created the Community Results Group.<P>

"There's tremendous fragmentation in the environmental movement. I basically see
it as there's those who are focused on problems versus those focused on
solutions." she observes. "When you're problem-oriented you become an expert in
the problem, not the solution."<P>

The Community Results Group is an experiential learning course
teaching participants to focus their energies and attention on results that they
want to create.
<P>
"The nucleus of the Community Results Group was we wanted to do something about
solving the conflict between environmentalists and developers," Sue explains. "So
the first class was evenly divided between  environmentalists and developers and
then some neutral people like the chair of the chamber of commerce."<P>

During the six-week course, participants meet three hours weekly, engage in
homework assignments such as listening to tapes, writing in their workbooks, and
reading. Each person focuses on a vision for their personal life.<P>

"And what happens to everyone who takes the course is that during the six weeks
you start to see movement towards your results. And it gives you a real feeling
that you can really create your life as oppossed to having your life created for
you by other people," Sue continues. As individuals learn to implement these
strategies in their own lives, then they are able to apply similar strategies in
their work together.<P>

"People who seem light-years away from you, if you search long enough there are
areas of agreement and you can use that as the basis for beginning to build
trust. And then what happens is that there is moderating of the polarities."<P>

"You start by asking the group 'if anything in the world were possible what would
you want this to look like?' And so there you have your vision and then it's just
a matter of how you go about implementing your vision," she explains.<P>

"You have to really know what you've got now; be very clear about what your
vision of the future is; and don't necessarily focus on the process of how to get
there," Sue advises. "We may not know how all of this is going to happen but we
will all be open to all the possibilities."<P>

Sue hopes that more individuals working for the environment will adopt
results-oriented strategies. "We would all be more effective if we all came
together around solution-oriented projects."<P>

Along with adopting solution-oriented strategies, Sue hopes that the
environmental movement also will adopt strategies for assisting people to
personally connect with nature.<P>

"Earth Day itself doesn't need to be transformed because it's perfectly good as
what it is. But what I would be interested in is to make people aware how
disconnected they are from nature. That is really a more important change to
enable," Sue explains.<P>

"We ought to have Earth Day for community building, community reinforcement,
seeing all your friends," Sue continues. "With all the exhibitors, you can
certainly learn new things. So it's a level of involvement that is fine. But it's
not the most fundamental one that I think Earth Day could really mean."<P>

"A lot of the problems we have could be solved by people reaffirming their
connection with nature," Sue explains. "But most people don't realize that part
of their maliase is due to this disconnection. Nobody thinks about it in those
terms."<P>

"Little kids are connected to nature. And we tend to lose that as we get older.
But there is a fundamental connection.  I think the real purpose of Earth Day
ought to be to help people get back in tune with nature. So to me the ideal Earth
Day would not be what we do at the park. We'd all go lay on the banks of the
Pedernales River or do rituals to the sun," Sue laughs.<P>

"What I'm talking about now is spirituality and a spirit connection. When we talk
about environmentalists we're talking about community and politics. There are
different levels of discourse."<P>

With the coffee glasses cleared and the check paid, Sue concludes her thoughts.
"We need these paradigm shifts. Sustainability is entirely possible -- we can save
the earth through our choices."<P>

We walk out into the warm March day for me to take a picture of Sue. Smiling,
with a halo of sunshine around her, she hugs the nearest oak tree.<P>

<FONT SIZE=1>
