<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Environmental Holiday</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>



<IMG SRC="images/folio.gif" ALT="GreenBeat!" ALIGN=top WIDTH=456 HEIGHT=72><BR>
<P>



<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3>Environmental Holiday</FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>Is Earth Day like Christmas?</FONT><P>
by Max Woodfin<BR> 
<P>


</CENTER>

<FONT SIZE=+1>Do you remember where you were on the first Earth Day?  Even among ardent
environmentalists, April 22, 1970, was not quite a signal event in the manner
of the Kennedy assassination, the day Nixon resigned or the Challenger
disaster.<P>

		I happen to remember where I was, because I was doing exactly what I'm doing
right now: writing about Earth Day. I had an assignment to write a newspaper
article about the role of organized religion in the environmental movement.<P>

		One of the ministers I interviewed made a remark that at the time I laughed
at, but later found incredibly insightful. To paraphrase, he hoped  Earth Day
would not become to environmentalism what Christmas Day had become to
Christianity.<P>

        What did he mean?<P>
        
        There's a syndrome known as "once-a-year Christianity," for those who show up
in church around the holiday season but aren't seen the rest of the year. The
syndrome isn't limited to Christianity, it just happened to be a Christian who
provided the analogy.<P>

        I wondered how we had fared these 26 years in his judgment. I tracked him
down to a nursing home, where I was told he didn't have the energy for
telephone conversations.<P> 

        I tried to imagine what I would have reported to him, had we been able to
discuss the state of environmentalism.<P>

        The good news is that more people are aware of environmental problems today
than 26 years ago. In our country, we have clean air and clean water
legislation that has slowed and in some cases reversed pollution problems.
We've made advances in the general knowledge about the dangers of pesticides.
(But we're still exporting pesticides that are illegal in the United States.
That's environmental racism of the worst degree.) Superfund programs are
notorious for feeding lawyers and consultants, but a few hot spots are cleaned
up and we seem to be creating fewer new priority sites. We're recycling more,
reusing more and in some instances reducing the use of raw materials.<P>

		Some of the bad news is that an inordinate amount of our energy is directed at 
what the late Edward Abbey called the common cold of environmental pollution --
litter. I'm all for clean roadsides and tidy parks, but do you ever wonder if we
couldn't have found a more profound use for all that money that went into "Don't
Mess With Texas?" We've let the polluters lull us into a feel-good ethic; we
think if we spend a day picking up trash we're having an effect on pollution.
Until our collective consciousness realizes that it's mostly the stuff we can't
see that really hurts, we're much like those Christmas Day Christians.<P>

        What would the minister's advice be for Earth Day 1996? He would probably
tell us to celebrate the day, to enjoy the companionship of others who share
our values. I also think he would tell us to wake up the next morning and try
to make a real difference. Because he's a Christian, he would probably tell us
to be missionaries: to run for office ourselves, or help put good people
there; to get appointed to boards and commissions and advisory groups so that
our voices are heard on the inside as well as the outside.<P>

        He would tell us to write thoughtful letters to the editor; to demand clean
and safe working conditions; to be less wasteful. He would probably refer us
to his prophet and remind us that John Muir wasn't the first to muse about how
everything in this world is linked together.<BR>
_______________<P>

Max Woodfin is an Austin-based writer and editor who specializes in
environmental issues.<P>

</FONT>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>


&nbsp;<BR>



