<HTML> <HEAD>

<TITLE>Let the Earth Speak</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>



<IMG SRC="images/folio.gif" ALT="GreenBeat!" ALIGN=top WIDTH=456 HEIGHT=72><BR>
<P>



<CENTER><IMG SRC="images/pnc1.gif" ALT="Connecting With Nature"
ALIGN=left WIDTH=190 HEIGHT=184><P><BR>&nbsp;<BR> <FONT SIZE=+3><B>Let the Earth
Speak:</B></FONT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2><B>A 10-Minute Earth Day
Activity</B></FONT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2>From Michael J. Cohen and<BR>Project Nature
Connect</FONT><BR><FONT SIZE=+1><I>by Dan Horowitz</I></FONT>

</CENTER> <BR CLEAR=ALL>


&nbsp;<BR>

<font size=+1>Helping people to connect with nature and to heighten their sensory awareness,
Michael Cohen uses Project Nature Connect to revive natural instincts which have been
dulled by the phantasmagoric abstractions of modern life.  Cohen shows people 
that they are disconnected from the planet and from themselves, and to uses
ecotherapy to help them reconnect.  Cohen says Let the Earth Speak is "a sampling
 of the experience and thought in the project."<P>

The activity is planned in conjunction with Earth Day, but is intended to be used
any and every day. The activity only takes ten minutes, and although Cohen refers
to it as a "secret" method, it is not really hidden from us, except by ourselves.
The entire activity, as written by Cohen, can be seen from his <A
HREF="http://pacificrim.net/~nature">Project Nature Connect</A> Web page, but in
brief the idea is to communicate with nature.  Communication in this sense
is not of human language, however.  It is a deeper-brained activity that works
through sensory experience.<P>

The first part of the activity is to admit or realize that communication without
language is possible, and indeed foremost in nature. Admit and accept this
challenge.  Then, Cohen tells us, after realizing that Nature speaks to us,  go
to nature and listen.  He suggests going to "the most unspoiled natural
environment available to you, be it a potted
plant, weed, pet, backyard, park, or sanctuary."  Try to know the place or
object without words, by seeing it, listening to it, and feeling it.  Repeat
 the word "attraction" until you feel
an attraction to the object or place.  Note how good the attraction feels, then
try to express it in written language.  Then, Cohen instructs, "read your statement 
to yourself with others and/or share it with others."
He offers you a chance to post your statement to share with others online, anonymously 
if you wish.  Many people
have already submitted their experiences.
  Finally, Cohen asks that you reflect on the experience to find its meaning in your 
  life.<P>

The Earth Day activity is based on years of experience Cohen has gained from living and
working outside and from the lessons and therapies he has used to reinforce his
instincts.  He has written several books and numerous articles on the subject and
many people have used his methods to reconnect with nature.  Cohen considers his
ecotherapy public domain.  He says anyone who uses his methods "owns" them and
can use them any time. Because Earth Day is supposed to be a day for reviving
environmental and ecological consciousness, the activity Cohen suggests is
especially relevant.<P>

Millions of people will be doing things for Earth Day and the week around it, but
even in these activities most of these people will probably be awash in the
symbolic world of language.  Language is a human invention so its necessary to go
behind it, to the natural world we know through our sensations in order to connect with
nature. There are more than just the five
sensations we usually consider.  Cohen says we have more than 50 sensations, and
he includes color, thirst, hunger and the desire to breathe along with the
traditional sensations of sight, hearing, smelling, etc.  Opening ourselves up to
these less recognized sensations and to the Earth in the process is a way to heal
ourselves.  The stress we feel in our daily lives is often a sign that we've
become disconnected with natural processes.  It can be alleviated through
conscious communion with nature.<P>

Cohen's Earth Day Activity and the other
activities he teaches aim to alleviate this stress, as a way and form of
meditation. There are essentially two parts to our brains, Cohen notes, the old
brain limbic system and the new brain, or neo-cortex.  Language is a function of
the neo-cortex which surrounds the older, sensation-processing limbic system. 
Because our sensations are associated with the limbic system, which developed
earlier in evolution, we have been connected to nature longer through our senses.  
"We have injured our sensory inner nature to the point that we are insensitive
to reality, and are thereby runaway," says Cohen. "The new brain is disconnected 
from the old brain by language."<P>

On an evolutionary scale, our ability to mediate our sensory experience with
language is newer, and subordinate.  However, Cohen says, we have increasingly
become reliant on our new-brain processing, largely because we spend 95 percent of
our lives indoors and because we know nature for 99 percent of our adult lives
through stories and pictures of nature, and not from nature itself. Pictures and
stories of nature are no substitutes for sensory experience of nature.  Stress
is largely a result of people trying to make this substitution, Cohen says.<P>

People become stressed because of incongruencies between the two parts of their
brains.  For example, quickly say the color of each of the following words
outloud:<P> <CENTER><IMG SRC="images/connect.gif" ALT="Word Color Test"
ALIGN=center WIDTH=81 HEIGHT=80></CENTER><BR CLEAR:ALL> Cohen uses this test to show that most people 
will say the name of the word before its color.  Until
they read correctly the word green, which is written in green ink, people report
feeling stressed. This comes, Cohen says, because people sense the correct color,
but the verbal label contradicts it.  He
says teaching people to be aware of the differences between their sensations and
their language processing teaches them to be more aware of how they are experiencing 
the world.  Greater awareness is the way to greater connection and greater connection
is the way to less stress.<P>

Let The Earth Speak, Cohen's Earth Day activity, is a way to accomplish the same
stress-reducing goal. Go to <A HREF="http://pacificrim.net/~nature">Project Nature
 Connect</A> to read
the Earth Day Avtivity in full and spend a little well-needed and well-deserved
time reconnecting to nature, today and especially on Earth Day.  Then, send
your comments to Micheal Cohen and read what others have said about their
experiences of connection.<P>

<FONT SIZE=1>(Note: The title artwork was done by Mimbres Indians about 1000 A.D)<P></FONT>
<BR>



