<HEAD>

<TITLE>Colleges with a Purpose</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>



<IMG SRC="images/folio.gif" ALT="GreenBeat!" ALIGN=top WIDTH=456 HEIGHT=72><BR>
<P>



<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3>Colleges With A Purpose</FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>Making A Better World</FONT><P>
by Miriam Weinstein<BR> 
ENVJOBS-L Listserv Manager <BR>
editor, Making A Difference College Guide: Outstanding Colleges to Help You 
Make A Better World<br>
</CENTER>

<P>
<font size=+1>

Do you feel your life has a purpose? If your purpose is healing, to help heal
life on this planet, please don't wait, or figure that someone else will do it.
You are truly needed.
<P>
Are you thinking about what kind of work you really want? Maybe your service is
to become an environmental lawyer, a policy planner. or to implement greener
manufacturing processes. Maybe your integrity is to develop sustainable forestry
plans. Maybe it's to help inner city kids make it through college.
<P>
Maybe you'll
even do that by becoming wealthy, and having money to donate. Maybe it's to write
about indigenous cultures, and help protect them and their knowledge. Perhaps you
want to teach. 
<P>
Maybe you don't have a clue, you just know you want to make a
difference. But you do know the right college education can make a vital
difference.
<P>
Your college choice process then is framed around very different questions than
most people ask themselves. It's not merely "Will I get a top education, or
a prestigious name education, how's the football, will it get me a decent or a
top paying job, or, even, will this get my parents off my back?" 
<P>
Your questions
are "will this college help me figure out what my work is," or "will this college
provide me with what I need to do my work to make a better world," and "does this
college support my values?"
<P>
And for each of you, what you need may be very different. Some of you may need
technical skills, some of you will want colleges rich in community based
service-learning, some of you may be planning on graduate school, while some may
need emotional healing and nurturing. 
<P>
The truth is, however, most of you probably
don't know exactly what you need - and you don't have to. Life's path often has
a way of revealing itself in slow twists and turns, and other times, in a moment
of sparkling insight.
<P>
When you are considering a college look at all the usual things: its academic
caliber, its location, majors and courses, and accessibility of professors. But
also learn if it has an ethic of service, concerns for peace and social justice,
an environmental focus, and how these concerns are brought into the classroom and
the world. How strong is the college on interdisciplinary and experiential
education? 
<P>
Then ask yourself - will this college give me what I need in order to
fulfill my purpose? I believe  if you want to use your education to make a better
world, it's a great advantage to attend a college where you really fit in.
<P>

There
are nearly 100 distinctive colleges and programs profiled in the book <B>Making A
Difference College Guide</B>. These colleges can
really direct you, give you the skills, tools, self-trust, and connections you'll
need. 
<P>
Colleges in <B>Making A Difference College Guide</B> are committed to and actively
engaged in helping solve our world's complex and pressing needs, both in and out
of the classroom. There are state colleges and universities, tiny independent
colleges, innovative schools, summer institutes, all kinds of programs. You can
take courses taught by teams of teachers from different disciplines, or design
you own major incorporating your own interests in your own particular way. 
<P>
One
things for sure: all the colleges you'll read about offer a vital, relevant
education. Reading this article will give you an idea of what to look for at any
college you are considering. 
<P>
Find a college with opportunities to learn while
doing service, and get college credit at the same time. Imagine working in a
health clinic in a remote part of Nepal, assisting migrant laborers in the South,
teaching sustainable agriculture in Central America,  or building water cisterns
at a school in the African countryside. 
<P>
You might help monitor a local river for
pollution using a new experimental technique, save a threatened species such as
the peregrine falcon, or sail on a clipper ship to study marine mammals. You
might design urban affordable housing, or erect a building out of straw bales.
<P>
You can spend two weeks at a Mayan village, study in Ecuadoran rainforests,
student teach at Native American reservations, tutor inner city kids, or have a
say in local development plans in Maine. 
<P>
College students who are out of the
ivory tower get a truly interdisciplinary real wor! ld education, the opportunity
to try out their career interests, and job contacts which often turn into a job
offer upon graduation.
<P>
<B>Making A Difference College Guide</B>  emphasizes meaningful career-oriented studies.
The more specialized your area of study, the easier it is to find work. Experts
are quick to note, however, the more "liberal" or broad your studies are, the
more flexible you'll be in your career opportunities over the years. And although
studies such as social work, peace, urban planning, and natural resources are the
ones listed in the book- students who major in traditional liberal arts such as
English gain critical thinking skills beneficial to an environmental career, or
specialize further in graduate school. 
<P>
Another source you can look at is
<B>Peterson's Education for the Earth</B>.  This book looks at many different
environmental majors at colleges nationwide - but it does not take into
consideration the culture of the college. There are substantial advantages at the
smallest hidden-gem college as well as the Ivy Leagues. 
<P>
Many of the socially
committed colleges are small, undergraduate-centered, and have approachable
faculty who care more about teaching than research. Universities, on the other
hand, offer a mind-boggling array of majors, greater opportunities to participate
in advanced research, and vast resources. 
<P>
Many parents fear that making a
difference means a life of poverty. We all know that nowadays, a college degree
doesn't guarantee a job, much less a secure, interesting or high paying one. It's
also true that if you're looking to make a better world, and if you are
persistent in seeking it out, there is a meaningful career waiting for you. 
<P>
Your piece of the
puzzle could be an essential one for determining what kind of a future you and
the generations to come will have. 
<P>
If you parents need some prodding to be
supportive, perhaps you can get them to pick up a copy of <B>Earth in Mind</B> by
Oberlin professor David Orr, published by Island Press. This is a deeply
thoughtful book about  higher education - and it just may help do the trick.
<P>

Ultimately it may not matter how prestigious a college is, what matters is if it
is the right college for you. 
<P>
For you personally, for the world around you, the
choices now before you are pivotal ones. It's not the schools prestige, but your
wish to count for something that will matter in years to come. 
<P>
Choose a college
that will guide and support you, while giving you the tools you need to give the
best within you, and you'll be well on your way to contributing to a better
world.
<P>
<A HREF="tips.html">Practical Tips on How to Choose A College</A>
<P>
<CITE>Miriam Weinstein is the editor of Making A Difference College Guide, Outstanding
Colleges To Help You Make A Better World (4th editon) published by Sageworks Press. 
For more information call (800) 218-4242.
</CITE>
<P>
</FONT>
