<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Pathways to Involvement</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>



<IMG SRC="images/folio.gif" ALT="GreenBeat!" ALIGN=top WIDTH=456 HEIGHT=72><BR>
<P>

<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+3>Pathways to Involvement</FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>Getting Involved in Community-Oriented Environmental
Activities</FONT><P>
<B>by Justus Baird</B><BR>
Coordinator Rice University Student Environmental Conference &<BR>
Volunteer for Citizens' Environmental Coalition<BR>
</CENTER>

<FONT SIZE=+1>
<P>

<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="images/earthand.gif" WIDTH=55 HEIGHT=61 ALT="Earth in Hand">

Planting trees, designing Web pages, leading hikes, writing news 
articles...These are but a few of the many things you can do to help out 
a community environmental organization.  Almost every single 
environmental group in your community will have a way to use volunteers 
or interns, and all you have to do is ASK them.<P>

In general, there are two levels of volunteering, short-term or 
single-event activities, and longer term intern type work.<P>

<H4>Short Term Opportunities</H4>
Many environmental groups need help with big, well-publicized events.  
This might be an Earth Day activity, fundraising event, or clean-up day.  
Many areas have local 'beautification days,' which require much more than 
simple manual labor.  Groups need volunteers to help out with the event's 
organization, publicity, and staffing.  Often they will require a 
short-term commitment of only a few hours a week for a few weeks.  In 
return, you'll usually get to meet some really exciting people, learn 
about how big events are organized behind the scenes, and give something 
back to the environment.  You can also use these events to learn about a 
group that you are interested in working for.  Sometimes, short-term 
volunteer opportunities can lead to intern positions, good contacts, and 
even a good job. <P> 

<H4>Getting Involved</H4>
How do you find out about these activities?  The best way is to keep your 
eyes and ears open - many events are publicized in local papers, 
newsletters, or on the radio.  If you don't hear about an activity in 
time to help with the planning, be sure to go to the event and introduce 
yourself to the people who look like they're in charge.  Tell them you'd 
like to volunteer, and you should see their eyes light up.  Any 
legitimate environmental group will ask you for your phone number if they 
don't ask you to help out right then.  And if they don't call you, it's 
not because they don't need your help - they probably just lost your 
number.  Call them back and see what volunteer opportunities are 
available.  <P>

        Another good way to get involved is to call your local volunteer 
center - just look up the number in the white pages.  Environmental 
groups, especially larger ones, often use volunteer centers to get 
community help for an event.  Many local volunteer centers will ask you 
what type of volunteer activities you're interested in, and then they'll 
match your request with the available opportunities.<P>
        The key here is to be outgoing - no group is going to call you up 
and ask you to volunteer if they don't know who you are.  Be persistent.
<P>

<H4>Long Term Options</H4>
Volunteering for a community environmental group on a longer term basis 
can often be more rewarding to you and the group.  Many local grassroots 
organizations are in a constant struggle for manpower, energy, and 
funding.  You can help them out by volunteering your time or expertise. <P> 

<H4>What Are Your Options?</H4>  
Often people are interested in volunteering for an environmental group - 
any group.  How do you know what opportunities are out there?  Here's a 
partial list of what might be available in your area:<P>

<UL>
 <H4>Small Issue-Oriented Local Grassroots Groups</H4>
Often small groups of citizens get together to form a group with a single 
purpose - to promote clean water or organic gardening, publicize the 
dangers of a hazardous waste site, or care for injured animals, to name a 
few examples.  These organizations have a crucial role in protecting our 
environment, and can be very rewarding to work for.  These groups 
sometimes are run out of membersU homes or offices, but every group is 
different.<P>

<H4>Established Coalition and Quasi-Governmental Groups</H4>
These organizations are usually a little older and better established.  
They are less activist, but probably have better funding, an office, and 
more contacts.  Also included here are groups that get both public and 
private funding.    <P>

<H4>Local Chapters of National Groups</H4>
The Sierra Club, Clean Water Action, Environmental Defense Fund, National 
Audubon Society, Campaign for the Environment (PIRG), and many other 
national environmental groups have local offices around the country.  
Their staff is professional, and their mission usually well-defined.  
Sometimes volunteers for these groups can be hired later on for a more 
permanent position. <P>
</UL>

<H4>OK, So What Would I be Doing?</H4>
Volunteering or interning for any of the above groups includes a wide 
variety of office related tasks.  You will often be asked to fill a 
number of roles, like answering phones, writing articles for newsletters, 
doing bulk mail, managing a member database, or planning a fundraising 
event.  Even though you might be stuck in an office, your help is 
crucial.  Students, especially college students, are very useful in these 
roles for a number of reasons.  First, they can work odd hours for little 
or no pay.  Second, and more importantly, students often have computer 
skills that many older activists don't have.  Simple things like creating 
a database, laying out a newsletter, or designing a web page can seem 
like insurmountable tasks for small groups with little computer literacy.<P>


<H4>Forget the Office, I Want To Work Outside or With Animals</H4>
If you'd rather not work in an office or as an activist, there are 
opportunities to volunteer with nature oriented groups.  For 
instance, most arboretums and nature centers need volunteers to lead 
nature hikes and other educational activities.  Often called docents, 
these volunteers are trained by the center and can make a visitor's 
experience much more meaningful.  Another opportunity is to find a local 
animal shelter, where you might have the chance to work with injured or 
misplaced wildlife.  There are groups that take care of everything from 
dolphins to cats to owls.  Finally, most areas also have plant and 
organic gardening groups that need your help as well.<P>

 
<H4>What's In It For Me?</H4>
You probably want to volunteer or intern for noble reasons, like simply 
helping out the environment.  But the fact is you will get many tangible 
and intangible rewards by working for any of these groups.  Crucial job 
skills, like phone and office communication, writing, fundraising, and 
initiative are high on the list.  Another big plus is contacts; more so 
than in other fields, working in the environmental sector is sometimes 
managed by who you know.  This doesn't mean that new people can't get 
involved, but it does mean that when looking for new hires, most groups 
like to look for people who already have experience, especially from 
volunteering for their own group.  On the soft side, you'll find that 
volunteering for community environmental groups will earn you good 
friends and lots of  personal satisfaction.   "Working on the front 
lines" will make you proud of what you do.  Finally, you'll be helping 
the environment - your environment - every hour that you work.<P>
 
<H4>How Do I Get In?</H4>
Finding a good volunteer or intern position can sometimes be exasperating 
- but don't give up.  Most groups are afraid of spending time training a 
volunteer, only to find that they can't give as much time as originally 
agreed upon.  Some good places to look for these positions include 
volunteer centers, university financial aid offices, and each 
organization's newsletter.  If there is a coalition group in your area, 
contact them to find out if they know of opportunities in other groups.  
They can also give you a list of groups in your area and how to contact 
them.  Increasingly, environmental groups are getting web pages, so 
surfing may turn up something as well. <P>
</FONT>

<FONT SIZE=1>
