<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Environmental Jobs</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>



<IMG SRC="images/folio.gif" ALT="GreenBeat!" ALIGN=top WIDTH=456 HEIGHT=72><BR>
<P>



<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3>ENVJOBS-L</FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>A Public Forum For Global Position Announcements</FONT><P>
by Bernhard Lorenz<BR> 
ENVJOBS-L Listserv Manager <BR>
Manager of <a href=http://www.iconsult.at/> Internet Consult</a><BR>and
Technical Contact for  the
<a href=http://www.cedar.univie.ac.at/> International Society for
Environmental Protection</a>.<br>
</CENTER>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>


&nbsp;<BR>

<font size=+1>
<p><b>Introduction</b><p>

</font>
The envjobs-l has been created due to heavy demand for a separate job list on
<b>enveng-l</b> (enveng-l@cedar.univie.ac.at). 
<a href=http://www.cedar.univie.ac.at/> CEDAR</a>, Europe's biggest 
Online Environmental Exchange, already hosting mailing lists with 
several thousand people,
agreed to start another list, for job announcements and resumes only:<p>
<b><i>
envjobs-l@cedar.univie.ac.at<p>
</b></i>

Since its creation in spring 1995, envjobs-l has attracted more than 4200
subscribers looking for and offering jobs.<p>
<p>
Subscription and posting to the list are free, and position
announcements as well as resumes are sent out once a week (usually each
Friday).
<p>
<hr><b>
<p><font size=+1>
Who is on the list?<p>
</b>
</font>
Naturally, most people on the list are located in the United States, followed
by subcribers from Europe. Nevertheless there are a few hundred people
who joined the list from Asian and South American countries.
<p>
Most people apparently are either students close to graduating or receiving
their Masters or Doctorates and are now trying to use this media to increase
their chances of finding a well-paying job in the environmental field; or they
are persons
who have already worked in an area for some time and are now trying to either
find a new job or to improve their current position by moving up the career 
ladder.<p>

It may be interesting to mention that despite the fact that the majority seems
to be looking for jobs, the number of job announcements being posted to the
list by far exceeds the number of resumes sent to us.<p>
<p>
<hr><b><font size=+1>
<p>

What is being posted?<p>
</b></font>
<p>
Job vacancies being posted are from a variety of different fields in the
environmental job sector.<p>
<p>
One has to distinguish between jobs in the public or academic area and
announcements for vacancies in the private sector. Where offers in the academic
or public area seem to be very widespread in terms of required experience (like
<i>about-to-graduate</i>, <i>doctorate</i> etc.), announcements from private 
companies
mainly regard jobs for senior executives. One cannot generally determine the
proportion of private sector jobs being offered, but a good estimate would
probably be - from reading the announcements - 15 to 25%. The main part is
being made up by academic and public sector vacancies that tends to cover a
bigger percentage of people looking for jobs in the environmental area.<p>
<p>
<hr width=50%>
<b><i>
Academic and public sector announcements<p>
</b></i>
<p>
The most predominant jobs being offered are those for ecologists. Job vacancies
range from internships over postdoctoral positions to research associates
and fellowships as well as assistant professorships. There does not seem to be
an area of ecology specifically sought for, instead I have seen announcements
for many kinds of branches of ecology, like
forest ecology,
 wildlife ecology
and insect ecology, to only name a few.<p>
<p>
Besides ecology announcements, biology positions are quite frequent. The jobs
being offered are, in general, similar ones as for ecologists, although the
main area seems to cover research associate positions, whereas internships and
assistant professorships are posted less frequently.<p>
<p>

<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="images/engineer.jpg" WIDTH=179 HEIGHT=124 BORDER=1
ALT="Engineers">
Ecologist and biologist positions make up for about half of the public and
academic field, the other half is more or less equally spread between GIS
specialists, environmental engineering, and environmental studies and policy.
Least often I receive announcements for environmental chemistry, botany,
environmental health and similar areas.<p>
<p>
Concerning the location of the jobs being offered, it is only natural
that the big majority are in the United States,
although there are also vacancies in other countries, like one-year-internships 
in South America, Asia etc.<p>
<p>
<hr width=50%>
<p><b><i>
Private sector announcements<p>
</b>
</i>
As opposed to the academic and public sector vacancies, private sector job offers
mainly
tend to address people with several years of experience, looking for senior
executive positions.<p>
<p>
Jobs being offered include program coordinators for individual departments
of big companies as well as executive directors for enterprises operating in
the environmental field. <p>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<font size=+1><b>
Remarks
</font></b>
<p>
Please note that this short article is just an overview of the various kinds
of announcements being sent to the envjobs-l list and 
what I can deduct from these announcements.
The present situation seems to be that
there are quite a few ecologist and biologist positions available, but 
 depending
on the market structure, especially in the United States, this situation may
change very quickly during the next few months. 
<p>
If there is demand, I can offer
a more comprehensive view with more statistical data on the jobs being offered
through our list.<p>
<p>
<HR>

To subscribe to the ENVJOBS-L list:<P>

1. address an email message to listproc@pan.cedar.univie.ac.at <BR>
2. leave the
subject line blank <BR>
3. in the body of the message type subscribe ENVJOBS-L
"yourfirstname yourlastname" <P>
<h5>
<I>
