<HEAD>

<TITLE>GreenBeat! Sprockets</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<IMG SRC="images/folio.gif" ALT="GreenBeat!" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=456 
HEIGHT=72><BR>

<H2>Earth Facts</H2>

<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="images/tinyglobe.gif" WIDTH=19 HEIGHT=17 ALT="Globe">
The current world population is 5,745,355,654 - as compared to 2,555,898,461 in 1950 and 
a predicted 5,772,351,016 in 2000 and  9,362,488,099 in 2050. (U.S. Bureau of the Census).
<P>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="images/tinyglobe.gif" WIDTH=19 HEIGHT=17 ALT="Globe">
In the U.S., 60 to 70 metro areas fail to meet air quality standards for
one or more pollutants, affecting some 59 million Americans. (EPA)
<P>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="images/tinyglobe.gif" WIDTH=19 HEIGHT=17 ALT="Globe">
Nitrogen oxides (NOx - key contributors to acid rain) have increased by 14 percent
since 1970. (EPA)
<P>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="images/tinyglobe.gif" WIDTH=19 HEIGHT=17 ALT="Globe">
More than 40,000 children under 5 years of age die each day from malnutrition and
related causes. That figue represents one child every 2 seconds. (UNICEF)
<P>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="images/tinyglobe.gif" WIDTH=19 HEIGHT=17 ALT="Globe">
While energy efficiency has improved considerably, total U.S. energy consumption
increased by 27 percent from 1970 to 1993. Americans are driving more - total
vehicle miles more than doubled from 1970-93. (EPA)
<P>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="images/tinyglobe.gif" WIDTH=19 HEIGHT=17 ALT="Globe">
In some countries 40% of the children die before reaching age 5, mostly from
water and nutrition related causes. (National Academy of Sciences)
<P>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="images/tinyglobe.gif" WIDTH=19 HEIGHT=17 ALT="Globe">
In Africa 5 million children die each year and another 5 million are crippled for
life due to hunger and malnutrition (United Nations)
<P>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="images/tinyglobe.gif" WIDTH=19 HEIGHT=17 ALT="Globe">
From 1970 to 1993, U.S. solid waste production increased from 122 million tons,
or 3.2 pounds per person per day, to 207 million tons, or 4.4 pounds per person
per day, more than any country in the world. (EPA)
<P>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="images/tinyglobe.gif" WIDTH=19 HEIGHT=17 ALT="Globe">
The list of threatened and endangered species has grown to more than 700. Of these,
the populations of only 38 percent were stable or improving as of 1992. Two
percent are now extinct, 33 percent are still in decline, and the status of 27
percent is unknown. (EPA)
<P>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="images/tinyglobe.gif" WIDTH=19 HEIGHT=17 ALT="Globe">
For each child under 15 in the U.S. there are another 21 children in developing
countries. On the average an American child can expect to live 15 years longer
and consume more resources in his lifetime than those 21 combined. (Population
Reference Bureau)
<P>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="images/tinyglobe.gif" WIDTH=19 HEIGHT=17 ALT="Globe">
The U.S. Department of Interior's new National Biological Service has identified 126
endangered or threatened types of ecosystems: 45 forest types, 51 types of wetland systems, 35 grassland/savanna/barrens, 15
aquatic ecosystems, and 10 shrubland types. (EPA)
<P>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="images/tinyglobe.gif" WIDTH=19 HEIGHT=17 ALT="Globe">
Worldwide, atmospheric levels of carbon dioxide have increased by nine percent
since 1972, raising concerns about climate change . Such emerging global threats
will require better scientific understanding and international cooperation in the
future. (EPA)
<P>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="images/tinyglobe.gif" WIDTH=19 HEIGHT=17 ALT="Globe">
Half the people in the world lack access to an adequate supply of safe water. In
rural areas only 29% of the people have access to safe water. (Church World
Service)
<P>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="images/tinyglobe.gif" WIDTH=19 HEIGHT=17 ALT="Globe">
80% of all disease in the world can be traced to drinking from and washing in
contaminated water supplies. (World Health Organization)


