<HEAD>

<TITLE>Problems of Elimination</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>



<IMG SRC="images/folio.gif" ALT="GreenBeat!" ALIGN=top WIDTH=456 HEIGHT=72><BR>
<P>


<IMG SRC="images/think.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=271 HEIGHT=383 ALT="Thinker">
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3>Problems of Elimination</FONT><P>

by Marshall Frech
</CENTER>

<FONT SIZE=+1>

<P>
Every day Austinites flush nearly 70,000,000 gallons of drinking water down the
toilet.  But eliminating human waste doesn't necessarily need to waste so much
water nor endanger groundwater with the occasional leaking pipe.  Recent
innovations have improved the process of decomposing and dispersing effluent
on-site, or within the property line.  To the degree that these new on-site
alternatives are supported and implemented, they may help improve Austin's water
quantity and quality.<P>

Most Austin residents currently depend on a complex web of gravity fed sewerlines
to carry effluent to three treatment plants.  These plants run the wastewater
though an extensive series of decomposition and purification stages before
returning it to the Colorado River five miles downstream.  A number of private
developments operate smaller scale treatment plants but dispose of their effluent
into localized water bodies (three empty into Lake Travis) or over fields, golf
courses, etc.  Besides high water use, arguments against centralized sewers list
the environmental disruption and vulnerability of sewer lines.  Centralized
systems, however, are relatively cheap and publically maintained.<P>

Departing from these centralized systems are a whole class of on-site systems. 
By far the most common of these is the septic tank which collects solids while
passing the majority of the waste into the nearby soil.  Septic tanks work well
enough where soil porosity and organic bacteria are sufficient to disperse and
decompose the effluent's pollutants.  However, within the thin, rocky soils of
the Hill Country, the wholesale implementation of conventional septic systems is
a questionable practice.  "The thin, caliche-type soils in the Edwards Aquifer
region are generally low in organic matter." says Susan Parten of Community
Environmental Services, Inc.  "This can pose a problem over a subsurface of
fractured or Karstic limestone because adequate treatment might not be achieved
before the effluent reaches underlying aquifers or nearby streams."<P>

Septic problems have drawn increased attention to a variety of on-site systems
which begin sewage treatment in the initial collection tank.  For example, the
"aerobic" class of on-site systems introduces oxygen into the tank to begin the
decomposition process.  Determining the appropriateness of an on-site system is
dependent on a complex series of factors including soil depth, bacterial
richness, slope, vegetation and development density.<P>

With so many variables, understanding on-site systems may appear the domain of
white-coated scientists but Michael Kelly, of Clearwater Systems pooh poohs the
notion: "Our systems work with basic parts and principals, " says Kelly,  "Rather
than a true alternative, our tanks are more like a mini wastewater treatment
plant.  Human waste is already loaded with all the bacteria needed to break
itself down. The only thing we have to add is oxygen," Kelly said, "lots of it."<P>

Kelly's aerobic systems pump compressed air bubbles through the effluent before
it moves to two adjacent tanks for disinfectant and storage.  Dispersing the
treated effluent then becomes the task of creative engineering.  Lucia Athens, of
Earth Sky Designs, is a landscape architect working on new ways to use effluent
through a combination of soil absorption, evaporation and plant transpiration.
"One of the designs I'm currently working on directs wastewater toward a small
orchard and some shade vines that we've incorporated into the landscape.  An
added a rain water collection tank helps drive the system, offering the owner
increased independence and efficiency," says Athens.<P>

The sustainability of recycled wastewater make on-site sewage an attractive
option for a variety of green builders, but these systems have their own
challenges. The question of who owns and services on-site systems has yet to be
resolved and a minor maintenance schedule (changing filters and/or adding
occasional activants), must be adopted by the user.  On-site systems also cost
more and complicate the task of assessing the re-sale value of the home.<P>

These costs are part of the growing price tag of water quality.  The City's
Environmental and Conservation Services Department (ECSD) is currently reviewing
a range of on-site systems appropriate for residential use over the Edwards
Aquifer.  ECSD has also commissioned a study by the local engineering firm Loomis
& Associates to obtain more comprehensive data on all potential sources of
pollution in the watershed.  The City hopes to determine what degree of pollution
now appearing in the aquifer stems from septic systems as compared to private
treatment plants or urban and ranchland stormwater runoff.  This effort is
intended to allow the most appropriate, cost-effective controls to be retrofit
into the problem areas.<P>

Septic systems and other on-site waste disposal techniques have long been
suspected of  water quality problems because local regulation emerged only as
late as 1972.  Much development in the Barton Springs Contributing Zone,
especially along Highway 290, occurred before this period.  In 1983, Travis
County began requiring inspections and proper designs of systems.  To what extent
effluent can be successfully regulated remains to be seen, but the number of
variables to be considered promises to keep the human factor in that most basic
of human questions.<P>

Good bathroom reading on various alternatives, including compost toilets and
graywater alternatives, can be found in the book <B>Goodbye To The Flush Toilet</B>,
edited by Carol Hupping Stoner - available at your public library.<P>



