<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Dillo Dirt</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>



<IMG SRC="images/folio.gif" ALT="GreenBeat!" ALIGN=top WIDTH=456 HEIGHT=72><BR>
<P>

<IMG SRC="images/dillod.jpg" ALIGN=LEFT ALT="Dillo Dirt" WIDTH=246 HEIGHT=357 
BORDER=1>

<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3>
City of Austin's Innovative Wastwater Treatment Byproduct</FONT><P>
</CENTER>

<FONT SIZE=+1>

<P>
Creative alchemy: turning something worthless into something valuable. That's
what 
the City of Austin is doing with wastewater sludge. Scientifically known as
biosolids, 
euphemistically called "black gold," Austin calls their nutrient-rich byproduct
"Dillo 
Dirt &reg; ."<P>

Austin's Water and Wastewater Utility operates one of the most advanced
beneficial biosolids reuse facilities in the country.  Since its inception in
1987, the Hornsby Bend Biosolids Management Facility has become a nationally
acclaimed, EPA award-winning biosolids recycling facility, receiving more than 18
local, state and national awards for environmental excellence.<P>

Biosolids are a by-product of specially treated, stabilized and disinfected
wastewater that originated from household and pretreated industrial sources.<P>

The City of Austin reclaims this nutrient-rich organic material from millions of
gallons of wastewater it treats every day.  All biosolids produced are being
recycled through land application or composting.  This compares with a recycling
rate of less than 20% for household solid waste (garbage).  Biosolids are used
for everything from revegetating city landfills and soccer fields. The composting
humus is also sold to the public for improving residential lawns, flower gardens
and fruit orchards.<P>

Here's how the step-by-step process works:

<OL>
<LI>Biosolids Thickening Facility;<BR>
Each day, over 47 dry tons of primary and secondary waste-activated biosolids
arrive via an underground pipeline from the City's three wastewater treatment
plants.  A gravity thickening process separates water from biosolids in the
wastewater residuals to reduce volume and allow the biosolids more time to break
down in the digesters.<P>

<LI>Anaerobic Digestion;<BR>
Thickened biosolids are stabilized through a process called anaerobic (without
oxygen) digestion to reduce odors and pathogen levels inside eight 2 million
gallon tanks or digestors. Methane gas, a by-product of the process, is used to
power on-site electric generators and heat the digesters.<P>

<LI>Drying Basins;<BR>
Digested biosolids are pumped into 25 acres of concrete drying basins.  The
biosolids are turned and air dried with special equipment.<P>

<LI>Compost Program;<BR>
Over 50% of the dried biosolids are processed into a stable organic product
called Dillo Dirt. &reg; Treated biosolids are combined with bulking agents such
as
tree trimmings, yard waste and recycled Christmas trees and then formed into 6
foot high windrows.   Approximately 70,000 cubic yards of these bulking agents
from the City's "Don't Bag It" and "Curbside Recycling" programs are diverted
from local landfills annually, saving valuable space and greatly reducing the
cost of solid waste disposal for Austin residents.<P>

<LI>Land Application;<BR>
Approximately 45% of the dried biosolids are applied to a 300-acre on-site farm. 
Nutrients from the biosolids improve the production of feed corn, hay, pecans and
other crops.  A contract farmer harvests the crops and returns a portion of the
sales revenue to the City.  The program, regulated by the Texas Natural Resources
Conservation Commission, is currently being expanded to improve soil conditions
and revegetate the municipal landfill and other off-site agricultural locations. 
Process water and storm water from the site is also cleaned by a series of ponds
and an aquatic greenhouse before it is used to irrigate onsite farmland.

</OL>

<P>
