<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Big City Systems</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>



<IMG SRC="images/folio.gif" ALT="GreenBeat!" ALIGN=top WIDTH=456 HEIGHT=72><BR>
<P>

<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3>
Big City Systems</FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>The Basics</FONT><P>
</CENTER>

<FONT SIZE=+1>

<P>
It's not rocket science by any means. Treating millions of gallons of wastewater
a day, the City of Austin utilizes basic chemistry concepts.<P>

The processes and apparatus are simple: Screens to filter the big debris; settling
tanks for liquid/solid dissipation; mechanical aeration to supply oxygen to
aerobic bacteria that eats up the waste; chemical additives for disinfection. But
to treat the sheer volume requires sophisticated monitoring and reliable systems.<P>

The City of Austin's Walnut Creek treatment facility serves approximately 300,000
customers and has a processing capacity of 60 million gallons per day.<P>

An 11 mile cross-town interceptor, up to 96 inches in diameter, transports
wastewater to the facility by gravity alone.<P>


A central computer console monitors 2700 individual points throughout the plant,
relaying information to the operators and allowing equipment to be controlled
remotely.<P>

Sludge from the system is transported to the Hornsby Bend Biosolids Treatment
Facility (see <A HREF="dillo.html">Dillo Dirt</A> story). Some of the reclaimed water is used by the city
to water parkways and greenbelts, the rest is discharged into Walnut Creek, a
tributary to the Colorado River.<P>

The city uses a three-stage treatment system.<P>

<H3>The Treatment Process</H3>

<H4>Primary Treatment</H4>

Wastewater enters the plant at the headworks and flows through screens which
remove large objects such as sticks, trash, and paper. After screening the
wastewater flows into grit basins in which heavier inorganic materials, such as
sand, small stones and trash, are settled out and transferred to dump truck along
with the screenings. These are disposed of at the landfill.<P>

The flow is then measured in a special flume and continues to flow by gravity
into the primary clarifiers. Here a large portion of the remaining organic and
inorganic matter is settled to the bottom of the clarifier and pumped to the
sludge processing facility at Hornsby Bend. The wastewater is then received by
the flow equalization basins. This is not a treatment process but allows storage
of high flows so that a constant rate may be applied to the biological part of
the process.<P>

The primary treatment portion of the plant is totally enclosed of ordorous gases.<P>

<H4>Secondary Treatment</H4>

Wastewater is now pumped into the aeration basins where the activated sludge,
which is essentially a large mass of microorganisms, consumes the remaining
dissolved organic matter.<P>

In the secondary clarifiers, the bacteria and absorbed material settle out to be
recycled to the aeration basins. As the mass of microorganisms grow, a portion is
removed and pumped to the sludge handling facility.<P>

The wastewater now purged of at least 95% of the wastes, passes to the chlorine
basins where only enough chlorine is applied to disinfect it.<P>

<H4>Tertiary Treatment</H4>

To further reduce suspended solids, the wastewater flows through dual medial
filters, much like a drinking water treatment process. Then sulfur dioxide is
applied in a small dose to dechlorinate before discharging the effluent into
Walnut Creek.

<P>
<FONT SIZE=1>
