<HEAD>

<TITLE>Microbes & Wastewater</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>



<IMG SRC="images/folio.gif" ALT="GreenBeat!" ALIGN=top WIDTH=456 HEIGHT=72><BR>
<P>

<CENTER><H1><EM>Microbes and Wastewater</H1></EM>
<P>
<H2>A Brief Overview</H2>
<P>
By Leonard Lied
</CENTER>
<P>
&quot;Microbes R R Friends&quot;, to paraphrase a popular TV commercial.
A microbe or microorganism is any microscopic life form. Actually
microbes are all around us, even inside us. Without this basic
life form human life could not exist. Potentially harmful microbes
are called pathogens, but there are <U>billions</U> of microbes
that are helpful. From the simplest septic tank, which some of
you have in your yard, to the largest city sewer plant, microbes
are at work cleaning the water. They convert wastes to elements
that provide nourishment for plants which in turn produce food
for animals including humans. This is the concept of ecology,
recycling our waste and leaving the fewest possible destructive
materials behind.
<P>
Almost any waste that is produced ends up in our water. Dealing
with it is what the science of wastewater treatment is all about.
The decision for specific treatment methods employed is based
on how much waste has to be handled, the types of waste, and how
much land is available. Population, economics, climate, and where
the discharge can be routed are all part of the equation. The
discharge from treatment facilities eventually must either be
returned to the land or a body of water. Let's review a little
history.
<P>
With the beginning of the industrial revolution in the mid 1800's
factories sprang up. People moved to the cities to get jobs and
have a better life. Most population centers were located near
the oceans, lakes, or rivers. The waste from the heavy concentration
of people, plus that of the factories, was being dumped into these
waterways. Everything in the water began to die. In the early
1900's pioneers of ecology initiated the concept of treating the
water before discharging it into the natural water systems. It
was not until 1972, with the passage of the Federal Water Pollution
Control Act Amendments, that real control of the discharge of
wastewater began.
<P>
The oldest and perhaps best way to treat wastewater is in an oxidation
pond which is basically an area that will hold wastewater. Where
land usage permits this practice is still used today. After putting
wastewater into the pond three layers are naturally formed. Sedimentation
occurs first when the heaviest part of the waste, the solids,
fall to the bottom The middle layer is made up of dissolved solids,
a mixture of water and waste that is soluble in water. The top
layer is primarily water. Microbes already present in the waste
increase rapidly once this separation process has occurred. The
microbes most commonly employed in biological wastewater treatment
are separated into the following classes: bacteria, fungi, protozoa,
rotifers, and algae.
<P>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="images/pond1.gif" WIDTH=410 HEIGHT=206 ALT="OXIDATION-POND">
</CENTER>
<P>
<B>Aerobic</B> microbes need oxygen to survive. Fungi, Protozoa,
Rotifers, and algae all live in the aerobic (oxygen rich) layer
at and close to the surface of the pond. We depend on microbes
in this layer to consume the pathogens.
<P>
<B>Facultative</B> microbes can exist either in the presence or
the absence of oxygen. The facultative layer is a transitional
stage where some of the most complex processes occur. Many different
theories exist but the constant changes in the microbes themselves
present a real challenge in complete understanding.
<P>
<B>Anaerobic</B> microbes, primarily bacteria, many of them pathogenic,
live in an environment without oxygen. Anaerobes can decompose
many different types of organic and inorganic wastes. At the bottom
of the pond in the sediment or sludge you would expect to find
anaerobic (little or no oxygen) conditions
<P>
In each of these layers, or environments, different processes
of decomposition, metabolization, and digestion take place. Each
of the specific microbe types is doing its job of removal or conversion
of the wastes and provides food for other of the microbes in the

pond. Without sufficient oxygen in the surface layer or with the
addition of too much waste, the pond quickly becomes anaerobic.
The anaerobes produce noxious gases as part of the decomposition
process they perform. Many of these bacteria can also be harmful
to humans. It is in the aerobic layer where these gases and most
of the bacteria are consumed by the aerobic microbes. If the aerobic
layer is sufficiently healthy there are no odor problems and a
much more complete removal of waste and harmful bacteria is accomplished.
<P>
Getting enough oxygen into the water for this process to continue
has always been a challenge and is often <B>the</B> critical factor.
Wind and wave action add oxygen from the atmosphere. Some algae
contribute oxygen as part of their life cycle. Mechanical aeration,
pumping air into the upper layer of the pond, is the most commonly
used method. As the amount of air pumped into the water increases
so does the agitation. This disturbs the natural layers already
mentioned and causes some disruption of microbial processes at
work. Natural Oxygen Products produces AG 14, a mixture of aerobic
and facultative microbes that add large amounts of oxygen to the
water without the disturbance caused by aeration. In this way
a much more efficient and complete conversion of waste occurs.
The greater the level of oxygen the more effective the process.
<P>
Some algae types produce oxygen through photosynthesis taking
energy from the sun and nutrients and carbon dioxide from the
water. However rampant algae growth, called an algae bloom, can
completely cover a pond depriving it of atmospheric oxygen and
sunlight. When algae dies it consumes large amounts of oxygen
as it decomposes, often killing the aerobic layer. On a microbial
level AG 14 reacts with dying algae and other suspended solids
causing them to fall back into the anaerobic layer at the bottom,
where they provide additional food for anaerobic bacteria. This
process clears the aerobic layer allowing ultra violet light from
the sun to penetrate and assist in the destruction of pathogens.
<P>
The following pictures illustrate how AG-14 affected suspended
solids in an industrial oxidation pond.
<P>

<TABLE BORDER=0>
<TR>
<TH>
Before Treatment
</TH>
<TH>
After Treatment
</TH>
</TR>
<TR>
<TD>
<IMG SRC="images/before.jpg" WIDTH=225 HEIGHT=147
ALT="POND-PRETREATMENT">
</TD>
<TD>
<IMG SRC="images/after.jpg" WIDTH=225 HEIGHT=147 ALT="POND-AFTER-TREATMENT">
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P>

<P>
All biological wastewater treatment facilities use some version
of the principles employed in the basic oxidation pond. Variables
such as pH levels, chemicals (both in the waste and added by operators)
ambient temperature, retention time, and nutrients in the waste
have a dramatic influence on the microbial life which must be
sustained. A treatment facility operator processing 20 million
gallons per day faces countless problems trying to keep all of
these variables in balance.
<P>
Microbes acclimate to their environment rapidly. Most bacteria
reproduce by division. This cycle can be as short as 20 minutes
or as long as several days. Each succeeding generation evolves
toward better utilization of the food sources available. As man
produces more complex compounds microbial science becomes increasingly
important. Microbiologists continually research, modify and develop,
task specific microbes to address the breakdown of elements in
our wastewater. Mr. Al Gough, the founder of Natural Oxygen Products,
patent holder, and early environmentalist, has worked for more
than thirty years to isolate and produce microbes that have applications
in wastewater and air treatment, agriculture and aquaculture,
and veterinary and medical areas. The national trend has long
been toward large scale high-tech, high-cost solutions to many
of our problems. Only recently has there been a reexamination
of the simpler more direct natural approach.
<P>
<HR>
Article by:
<ADDRESS>
Leonard Lied - 
<B>NATURAL OXYGEN PRODUCTS</B><BR>
PHONE (915)833-2168<BR>
FAX (915)833-6795
<P>
<A HREF="mailto:llied@whc.net">E-Mail Leonard Lied    <llied@WHC.NET></A>
