<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chemical Engineering</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>



<IMG SRC="images/folio.gif" ALT="GreenBeat!" ALIGN=top WIDTH=456 HEIGHT=72><BR>
<P>

<IMG SRC="images/mark.jpg" ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=103 HEIGHT=144 ALT="Mark"><BR>
&nbsp;<P>

<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3>Career Profile</FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>Clean Water through Chemical Engineering</FONT><P>
by Mark Fitch
</CENTER>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>

<FONT SIZE=+1>
&nbsp;<BR>
When I was in my first few weeks of graduate school in Chemical Engineering, I
went to the various advisors and chatted with them about the projects they might
want me to work on.  At the time, I had very little preference for one field or
another.  However, I found one project very interesting.  It was very interesting
because the research was in the environmental field, and I thought it might be
neat to do research that made me feel like I was doing something, well, good.<P>

I was right.<P>

So I spent six years in graduate school working on this project.  It's pretty
cool.  What I've been developing is a method to remove chlorinated solvents from
ground waters.  Chlorinated solvents means chemicals that are typically used by
dry cleaners and machine shops as degreasers, which were found to be carcinogens
during the seventies and have since declined in popularity, a lot like disco. 
Ground waters means well water.  Half, or slightly more, of the U. S.  population
gets their drinking water from ground waters, and the most frequently found
priority pollutants are (ding!) chlorinated solvents.<P>

The best current way to remove these bad things is to pass the water through
activated carbon (you know those Brita clean water pitcher thingmabobs? 
Activated carbon.)  Activated carbon acts like a sponge.  Unfortunately, it has
similar properties - it can only take up so much stuff before it starts leaking,
and if you just let it set, it starts to drool like a St. Bernard.  So you take
your used carbon and throw it away.  It goes to a landfill, where the carbon
'drools' the pollutant right back into the ground and the groundwater.<P>

Now usually this isn't such a big deal, because the bacteria in the soil like to
eat up most drool.  Unfortunately, most of these chlorinated solvents aren't
eaten by anything.  That's because of the property that made them popular in the
first place - they don't burn.  Therefore bacteria can't get anything out of
burning them as food.  So these compounds hang around, and get back in the water,
and what have you accomplished but to move the problem to someone else's back
yard?<P>

As it happens, some bacteria are stupid, and are able to degrade these compounds.
 They don't get any benefit at all from doing it, but that's not our problem. 
Our problem is to get these bacteria to degrade lots of this stuff.  Well, that's
my problem.  Actually, that was the goal of my research - to use some of these
bacteria and develop a treatment system.  I've learned alot, and I think it is
possible that a real system will come out of this research, but I've more defined
what doesn't work (which has something to do with the six years, but I will admit
that Doom and Marathon had something to do with it too.)<P>

I do know that when the process works well, it costs about what the activated
carbon does, and it destroys the chemicals - turns them into chloride and carbon
dioxide and cell mass.  My advisors, Gerald Speitel Jr. and George Georgiou, are
continuing to pursue the work.<P>

As far as me, I think I'll look into using these bacteria underground (they
already exist most everywhere, it's just a question of getting them to prosper),
and look at genetically engineered bacteria for the same purpose.  I know a lot
of people are scared of genetic engineering, but having worked with genetic
engineers (you oughta see their train sets), I now know that what they are doing
is to use natural methods of moving bits of DNA around.  Sure, I'm scared of AIDS
and Ebola and multiple antibiotic resistant diseases.  Oh yeah, those were gifts
of nature, not genetic engineering.  But still, I do feel that genetically
engineered microorganisms (GEMs) will be widely accepted for many applications in
the near future (ten years?).<P>

Recently, during my interview with the department chairman of Civil Engineering
at the University of Missouri at Rolla (I've accepted the position, and will be
teaching environmental engineering), he asked why I wanted to be a professor.  My
response, the first thing that came to my mind, was to say that I wanted the
position because at the end of the day, I could feel like I had accomplished
something good - not merely that I had pushed forward the bounds of science on
any given day, or had educated someone, but because I would have the satisfaction
to have helped humankind.<P>

I can't say that I came to the environmental field from any burning desire to
protect nature or man, but now that I'm here, it feels pretty good.<P>



<FONT SIZE=1>
