<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Sink Think</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>



<IMG SRC="images/folio.gif" ALT="GreenBeat!" ALIGN=top WIDTH=456 HEIGHT=72><BR>
<P>

<IMG SRC="images/sink.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=203 HEIGHT=121 ALT="Sink?" BORDER=1>

<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3>Sink Think</FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>What Goes Down Comes Around</FONT><P>
</CENTER>

<FONT SIZE=+1>

What's dripping down your drain may come back to you again.<P>

While sinks and toilets are convenient waste receptacles, there are many common
household products that should never be flushed down a drain.<P>

Just one gallon of motor oil can contaminate up to 2 million gallons of drinking
water. Many household cleaners can also harm the environment, especially water
supplies.<P>

High phosphate levels can kill a river and all the life within it. Many
supermarket-variety laundry detergents contain phosphates. The average consumer
nationwide uses about 30 pounds of laundry detergent a year; all together,
Americans use about 8.3 billion pounds of dry detergents and a billion gallons of
liquid detergents each year! Some cities, including Austin, Texas, have banned
the sale of phosphate detergents, but many other communities have not.<P>

Many other household cleaning products contain harmful solvents and harsh
chemicals that destroy the natural processes involved in wastewater treatment
(see story on <A HREF="micro.html">microbes</A>).  It's not hard to tell which
are the most harmful - does the product cause your eyes to sting or water? do you
wince from the smack of the strong chemical odor? does it burn when it contacts
your skin? We are literally killing ourselves with cleanliness.<P>

Neither prescription nor over-the-counter medicines should ever be disposed of
down a drain. They also can kill the good bacterial microbes.<P>

Paints and even paint brushes shouldn't be cleaned in a sink. Along with harmful
solvents and resins, paints contain many additives including biocides,
fungicides, antifreeze, antisettling agents, fillers, catalysts, curing agents,
driers, emulsifiers, fire retardants, plasticizers and thickeners!<P>

Think before you pour waste down the sink. Only natural, food and human wastes
should be disposed in our sewer systems.<P>

Buy non-phosphate detergents. Use a trusty plunger and boiling water to unclog a
drain. Try earth-friendly cleaning products - they're less caustic and clean just
the same. Dispose of left-over paints and used motor oil through city or county
recycling/recollection programs.<P>

<FONT SIZE=1>

[Information gleaned from The Austin Environmental Directory, compiled and edited
by Paul Robbins.]<P>


<CENTER>
