<HEAD>

<TITLE>GreenBeat! Sprockets</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<IMG SRC="images/folio.gif" ALT="GreenBeat!" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=456 
HEIGHT=72><BR>

<H2>Wastewater Factoids</H2>

Source: <A HREF="http://www.tec.org/almanac/TXENVALMANAC.HTML">Texas Environmental Almanac</A>, 
Chapter 2 - <A HREF="http://www.tec.org/almanac/QualityCh2p1.html">Water Quality</A>

<P>

<IMG SRC="images/droplet.gif" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=8 VSPACE=10 WIDTH=19 HEIGHT=24>
In Texas, the combined municipal and industrial discharge of wastewater - about 21 
billion gallons per day - is enough to fill Texas Stadium (home of the Superbowl XXX 
Champion Dallas Cowboys) 27 times over with wastewater.
<P>
 
 <IMG SRC="images/droplet.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE HSPACE=8 WIDTH=19 HEIGHT=24>
20,477 million gallons of wastewater are discharged into Texas river basins daily.
<P>

<IMG SRC="images/droplet.gif" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=8 WIDTH=19 HEIGHT=24>
Wastewater flows from domestic sources average about 100 gallons per day for each 
person served.
<P>

<IMG SRC="images/droplet.gif" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=8 WIDTH=19 HEIGHT=24>
In a city of one million residents, about 200,000 lbs. of suspended solids are turned 
into sludge at the city's domestic wastewater plant each day.

<P>

<IMG SRC="images/droplet.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE HSPACE=8 WIDTH=19 HEIGHT=24>
Fecal coliform is the major cause of impairment in Texas streams and rivers.
<P>


<IMG SRC="images/droplet.gif" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=8 VSPACE=10 WIDTH=19 HEIGHT=24>
The Rio Grande, the river which forms part of the border between Texas and Mexico, 
serves as both the major source of drinking water and the principle recipient of 
wastewater for the region.
<P>

<IMG SRC="images/droplet.gif" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=8 VSPACE=16 WIDTH=19 HEIGHT=24>
Together, the Mexican border cities of Ciudad Juarez, Ojinaga, Ciudad Acuna, Piedras 
Negras, Nuevo Laredo, Reynosa and Matamoros discharge an estimated 175 million gallons 
of wastewater into the Rio Grande and Gulf of Mexico per day. About 112 million gallons 
per day is untreated, the remaining 63 million gallons receive only primary treatment.
<P>

<IMG SRC="images/droplet.gif" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=8 VSPACE=10 WIDTH=19 HEIGHT=24>
Since 1972, the amount of pollution dischaged in wastewater by domestic facilities 
has decreased about 70% in Texas. At the same time the amount of wastewater 
requiring treatment has increased by 85%.
<P>

<IMG SRC="images/droplet.gif" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=8 VSPACE=10 WIDTH=19 HEIGHT=24>
Different organic materials in wastewaters require different amounts of oxygen - commonly 
known as Biochemical Exygen Demand (BOD) - in order to break down and stablize the 
material. The greater the BOD, the greater the oxygen depleting effect of the wasterwater 
upon the receiving stream. The BOD of typical untreated domestic wastewater varies from 
100 to 300 milligrams per liter. Chicken blood from a food processing plant, on the other 
hand, might require from 1,000 to 4,000 milligrams per liter of BOD to treat.
<P>

<IMG SRC="images/droplet.gif" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=8 VSPACE=14 WIDTH=19 HEIGHT=24>
One of the best sources of information for the amount of toxics entering Texas waters is 
the Toxics Release Inventory (TRI). Under the federal Superfund Authorization and Renewal 
Act, manufactuing companies with 10 or more employees that use or manufacture more than 
25,000 lbs. per year of any of more than 320 toxic chemicals or compounds must file an 
annual report with the state.
<P>


