<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>GreenBeat! Profile</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>



<IMG SRC="images/folio.gif" ALT="GreenBeat!" ALIGN=top WIDTH=456 HEIGHT=72><BR>
<P>

<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3>Profile: Patricia DuBose Michael</FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>Teaching the Region - Permaculture</FONT><P>

<FONT SIZE=+1>by <B>Pamela Colloff</B></CENTER><BR>
<P>

<P><FONT SIZE=+1>Just outside the Austin city limits, where paved subdivisions
and traffic snarls give way to the Hill Country, lies Patricia DuBose Michael's
permaculture retreat. As a &reg; Permaculture instructor and bioregionalist, she wants
to make people fiercely love the place they live, to be as she puts it;
"territitorial."

<P>

<IMG SRC="images/patricia.jpeg" ALIGN=RIGHT ALT="Patricia" WIDTH=144 HEIGHT=211>



We should have roots in our bioregion, in our place, and feel like we belong,"
she says. If you have roots in the land and you find value there, you'll be a
better territorialist than anybody else. That tree in the parking lot that is
still alive that people have been paving around for years: there's a lesson
there."

<P>


Patricia sits on the sun-lit deck that overlooks the retreat's seven acres of
cedar-lined limestone.  The terrain is crisscrossed with swales: tiny man-made
dams that slow the flow of rainwater to prevent flooding and maximize rainfall. 
When she and her husband first purchased the retreat, they build these swales by
cutting the low branches from the land's juniper trees, trimming and bundling
them, and then positioning them along the land's inclines. 

<P>

<IMG SRC="images/swale.jpeg" ALIGN=LEFT ALT="Swale" WIDTH=272 HEIGHT=200>
Swales, she explains,
are "a way of managing water for long-term feeding of plants by creating little
regional aquifers. The water will hang there for a period of time. If there's a
large rainfall, water will slow down. It's like an irrigation system....You could
build them out of trash -- well, so called "trash" -- or blocks, or sticks, or
soil. Anybody can do it; you don't have to have any money." 

<P>

When she and her
husband bought the land, it "was a dense monoculture of nothing but juniper and
oak that we had to crawl through." Patricia and her husband did selective
harvesting, contoured the land, put in swales and larger retention ponds, and
planted around 5000 shrubs and fruit trees. 

<P>

"It's richer in any bioregion to
leave what you can of what's already on the ground and then integrate what you
want, rather than taking out and replacing," she explains. Swales can help to
maximize what is already growing in a bioregion. "A lot of times we already have
our crop, but we chop down our crop to try to grow something that's just puny in
that area. So we have to know enough about the native plants to know what is crop
and where we can get our living." 

<P>

This is one of the basic ideas behind
Patricia's permaculture classes. She instructs people on how to optimize their
bioregions and thereby become less dependent on manufactured drugs and processed
food, and learn what they might find in their own bioregion. In addition,
Patricia teaches her students guerrilla media, bioregional organizing techniques,
and personal and public health.

<P> 

"You're a bioregionalist if you think it's better
to cooperate around biological systems and to know and be bonded with the place
that you live," Patricia explains. "But &reg; Permaculture is a trademark, a
copyrighted word, and to use it, you have to be trained in a 72-hour
certification course. Anyone who's taken the course can instruct." 

<P>

Each course
teaches the basic tenets of permaculture as well as bioregional strategies that
are relevant to the issues of the participants' particular area. Patricia's
course in Baytown, for example, taught women union stewards from the Exxon plant
about personal health in relation to toxins and air quality, while the course in
West Texas that took place around a campfire taught about broad-scale grazing and
water infiltration. An inner-city course at a community center focused on
resources, the community, and traditional folk medicine. Other courses in urban
settings have even had a section on effective dumpster diving. 

<P>

"I try to teach
people what they need," she says. "I teach to any population that's interested,
and I work on training other teachers." 

<P>

Patricia's upbringing has a great deal to
do with her understanding of self-sustenance. She was raised by her grandmother,
who worked as a midwife around the Santa Fe railway yard near Wichita, Kansas.
"My grandmother practiced from a long tradition of women which she passed on to
me and our family, women who lived off the land and grew their food and medicines
and knew how to serve their populations." 

<P>

Outside of Wichita, Patricia explains,
"there was a mixture of poor people and new immigrants from all over the world,
so I got to sit at dinner tables with Chinese and Mexican traditional medicine
people, folk medicine people from Japan and the Balkans. I got a peek, through
childhood, of this very rich way that people have always lived having what they
needed around them, supporting them, including their communities." 

<P>

Patricia
stresses that people's connections to their surroundings have changed greatly
since her grandmother's time. "If you look in any cookbook from before the turn
of the century, there are recipes for medicines and how to make things for the
house," she says. "But if you look in a cookbook now, they require you to buy a
package of pre-mixed ingredients. You put three or four of those packets together
to make a 'recipe.' Not only does it make us dependent, it increases our
non-commitment." Patricia is deeply concerned with this rift between people and
their surroundings, noting that "now even the wildest gang member is quite often
afraid of nature. I knew a teenager once who actually freaked out when some weeds
and plants touched his leg because he'd never been around anything but paved
surfaces." 

<P>

Although she has previously taught in the university system as an
architecture professor, Patricia has grown wary of academia's impractical and
uninspiring lessons and teaching methods. "If whatever students are studying
isn't teaching them directly how to live on the ground and how to handle the
products of their own body -- their own waste water, their own possessions -- and
if it doesn't teach them really practical information about how to take care of
themselves or others, then they should get out of it. 

<P>

"Parenting isn't even
taught in the universities; that's the most important skill we've got going.
That's survival," she says emphatically. "Food and growing food is not taught.
Most university campuses are waste lands. I only know of only two universities
that grow food or that address the idea of edible landscaping in some
departments. I don't know of any universities that teach life skills...There
might be hope if universities taught these things, but very few of them teach
it." 

<P>

She adds, "We don't just need information, we need hope, and that's what the
universities aren't giving. If you get someone excited about taking action, but
they don't have the materials to work with, that can only breed greater
hopelessness." 

<P>

Getting territorial doesn't mean drawing a line in the sand.
"Anything that creates barriers is not in keeping with the laws of nature,
because nature doesn't have barriers, separations. Nature doesn't have hard
edges; it flows from one place to the other, and that's a healthy system. It's
like water. The minute you stop water, it becomes unhealthy water. If water's
flowing, it's healthy water, alive water. It's the same with us." Indeed,
Patricia shows how there is nothing less stagnant than a deep, long-term
committment to our land.

<P>
</FONT>

<FONT SIZE=1>
<CENTER>
<A HREF="toc.html">Table of Contents</A> |
