Last-Modified: Monday, 08-Jan-96 18:10:23 GMT
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 6151
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>GreenBeat! Profile</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>



<IMG SRC="images/folio.gif" ALT="GreenBeat!" ALIGN=top WIDTH=456 HEIGHT=72><BR>
<P>

<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3>Profile: Hal Strickland</FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>Intelligent Land Uses</FONT><P>
</CENTER>


<IMG SRC="images/coffee.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALT="Hot Tea" WIDTH=92 HEIGHT=100>
<FONT SIZE=+1>Looking intently into the warm, rippling water of his cup as he
stirs his morning tea, Hal Strickland is talking about swales, and soil and
symbiosis.

<P>

I'd met Hal just two nights before in the campfire light of a backyard potluck
dinner attended by an eclectic assortment of Austinites: community organizers,
environmentalists, artisans and muscians, journalists, small business owners, and
assorted bohemians. Asking to meet someone involved in bioregionalism, several
fingers point me in Hal's direction.

<P>

Now we're having breakfast at Magnolia Cafe and Hal is obviously warming into one
of his favorite subjects.

<P>

"A swale is a constructed slope to detain water. It can be little more than one
inch high, laid in contour with the land," Hal begins. "We have to stop rainwater
in its tracks. What arrives from the sky is the most abundant and the cleanest
water versus the water that travels miles to you, that's been treated,
chlorinated or pumped to you."

<P>

"In Austin, with an annual 33-35" of rainfall, the idea of a drought is testament
to our lack of awareness," Hal continues, pointing out that the area's abundant
rivers, creeks and springs are drying up due to the overuse of groundwater in the
Edwards Aquifer.

<P>

"Look at California with its much more restricted rain patterns. The miracle of
California agriculture is massive irrigation. It's destroyed many California
waterways. The Colorado used to support a delta and abundant life. Even the Sea
of Cortez has suffered."

<P>

Hal recounts visiting the little Mexican communities within the dead delta zone,
now a desert, where occasional floods can wipe out an entire village.

<P>

"You have to start with a plan," he says. "Utilize available rainfall by
constructing a land form, even on a microscale, such as a swale. If we could
cause our generous rainfall to percolate, our streams would flow year-round."

<P>

Hal steeps his tea with another cup of hot water as he begins describing his own
epiphany into permaculture, which he says teaches how to "take any piece of land
on the earth and consider it as human habitation while respecting the other life
living there."

<P>

Hal's own watershed event occurred in 1988 when he attended a two-week training
seminar with the permaculture pioneer, Australian Bill Mollison. "In two weeks I
was exposed to what I always wanted to learn in college. All these different
disciplines had not been knitted together before."

<P>

Understanding the complexities and interdependencies within natural systems and
agricultural techniques is the foundation of permaculture. The swales that save
rainwater also save soil. "Rain is driven by gravity. Washouts, runoffs carry
large amounts of sediment away. The bigger the runoff event the bigger the
damage."

<P>

"Take contour plowing," Hal continues, "the old-timers know it works but modern
growers are cutting down windbreaks that protect their fields from erosion."
Rather than reading the slope of the land and plowing to maximize its benefits
for soil protection and rain collection and direction, most fields are flattened
and plowed in straight rows.

<P>

"Modern farming is designed to maximize the consumption of industrial byproducts
like pesticides and fertilizers." While these techniques produce large harvests
and sustain agri-industries, "this big time agri-business burns off the microbial
life of the soil," Hal points out.

<P>

"But permaculture relies on the symbiotic relations within nature; cultivating
these complexities and relationships, " he says. "In permaculture you think 'how
many uses can this plant demonstrate?'"

<P>

"The sycamore tree that drops leaves is building the soil. If placed properly it
shades a house in the summer and lets in sun in the winter. It brings birds that
eat pests. It has a guild relationship with other tree species that grow best
when they grow together."

<P>

"In diversity, in this richness, there is more sustainability. In complex units
there is more opportunity for success than in singular-focused systems," Hal
notes from his own experience farming for 15 years in the Texas Hill Country.

<P>

Hal speaks admiringly of the Soil Conservation Service which in the 1930s taught
similar techniques to dust-bowl farmers. But this knowledge has been lost or
forgotten. Permaculture is reapplying such old-time knowledge in these newer
times when sustainability has never been more important.

<P>

"Did you know that when our highland lake dams (the damming of the Colorado River
in the Central Texas region) were constructed, 320 earthen dams were also
created?" Hal asks. "These systems of swales are now abandoned. But it was
intelligent, very intelligent."

<P>

</FONT>

<FONT SIZE=1>
<CENTER>
<A HREF="toc.html">Table of Contents</A> |
