<HTML> <HEAD>

<TITLE>Buy/Grow Local</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>


<IMG SRC="images/folio.gif" ALT="GreenBeat!"
ALIGN=top><BR> <P>

<IMG SRC="images/veggies.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALT="Veggies" WIDTH=180 HEIGHT=134>

<FONT SIZE=+3>Sustainable Food: Buying & Growing Locally</FONT><P>

<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+1>by Pamela Colloff</FONT><P>
</CENTER>

<FONT SIZE=+1>Why should you think locally, not globally the next time you're
hungry? Greta Hunter Watson, the Program Coordinator for Austin's Sustainable
Food Center, sees several distinct advantages to buying within your own
bioregion; not only does it keep food dollars in the local economy, but food is
fresher, cheaper, and healthier. 

<P>

"The fresher your food is," she explains, "the more vitamin content it has, the
better it tastes, the better it cooks, the less it deteriorates, and the less
you're apt to have to use pesticides or fungicides when you're shipping or
storing it."

<P>

By drastically limiting the distance that food has to travel and time it must be
stored, there is no need for farmers to add unhealthy additives that are passed
on to consumers. Fruits and vegetables that are shipped from other parts of the
country such as apples, bell peppers, cucumbers and eggplants are not only
frequently sprayed with pesticides, but are coated in canuba wax. This wax locks
in pesticides, making it difficult to wash off food thoroughly. 

<P>

Because of preservatives and wax, produce that looks fresh may actually be quite
old. "Many of the apples you see in the store from Washington are over a year old
-- they've been in cold storage," says Greta. By minimizing the distance that food
is shipped, farmers can offer their produce at cheaper prices by cutting down on
transportation costs, pesticides, and the amount of food damaged in transit. 

<P>

"We always try to buy organic, local produce first," said Greg Thibeaux, Produce
Buyer and Assistant Manager for the Wheatsville Food Co-op. "We put up signs
telling customers when things are Texas-grown, and they really respond to that."

<P>

In addition to encouraging stores and consumers to support local farmers and
ranchers, the Sustainable Food Center is responsible for turning a vacant lot
into the Eastside Community Farmers' Market. Every Saturday from May to October,
local farmers sell fresh fruit and vegetables to the East Side's economically
disadvantaged community which is frequently unable to obtain fresh produce. The
two East Side grocery stores are not always easily accessible for those who don't
have cars, and their produce is higher priced and less fresh than in other
neighborhoods. 

<P>

Adjacent to the Farmers' Market is the Eastside Community Garden, where two acres
are available to individuals, families, and organizations to organically grow
fruits, vegetables and flowers. The idea for the garden began when the
Sustainable Food Center found that one 4 x 16 foot garden in Austin can provide a
family of four with fresh fruit and vegetables every day of the year and save the
family $600 in grocery bills. Gardeners can also sell any surplus produce at the
farmers' market to increase their family income. 

<P>

In addition to the garden and market, the Cocina Allegre Food School teaches
low-income families how to prepare heathful meals on a shoestring budget. Local
chefs teach free six-week courses in English and Spanish, showing how to be both
nutritional and cook for no more than $1.20 per serving. 

<P>

The idea behind all of these projects, explains Greta, "is to unite rural and
urban groups. That's why with the farmer's market we have rural food for urban
people." The Center is also considering setting up an agriculture apprenticeship
program for East Side teenagers in which they would learn how to farm and live
sustainably.

<P>

"In the last 65 years, Texas has gone from over 80,000 farms owned by black
farmers to 3,000 farms owned by black framers," says Greta. "Farming is going out
of the hands of the ethnic minority. One of the ways to keep ourselves strong is
to encourage ethnic diversity in land management, as well as sustainability and
reducing the use of pesticides."

<P>

One group that is helping to achieve those goals is the Texas Sustainable
Agriculture Working Group, a coalition of more than 900 farmers, ranchers,
environmentalists, consumers, and public policy makers who are dedicated to
increasing public awareness of sustainable agriculture by disseminating
information, finding markets for their products, and encouraging public policy
that supports sustainable methods.

<P>

Another program that is raising public awareness in-state is the Texas Department
of Agriculture's Buy Texas campaign. Local fruits, vegetables, and meats have
stickers announcing that they are "Texas Grown." The 10-year-old program, says
the TDA's Susan Dunn, "Has been a huge success. There are now 750 companies
included." The Buy Texas program also includes the Vintage Texas program for
local wines and the Naturally Texas program for locally made clothes. Both
programs try to raise consumers' awareness of these products and encourage them
to buy locally.

<P>

In addition, in the coming year, the Austin-Travis County Food Policy Council -- a
partnership between the private sector and government -- is working towards making
unused public land available for farms and community gardens as well as assisting
existing small food stores, helping to develop new grocery stores and food
co-ops, and making it easier for people to access supermarkets. 

<P>

The Sustainable Food Center, which helps coordinate the Food Policy Council and
the Texas Sustainable Agriculture Working Group, will also work this year with
local schools to help improve school lunches by encouraging the use of fresh,
local produce. "This will stimulate local agriculture, reduce the amount of
chemicals in our children's food and, because it tastes better, increase the
amount of good food our kids eat," says the Center's publication <I>Food For
Thought</I>. The Center will also try to certify more farmers' markets to accept
food stamps and WIC coupons.

<P>

For more information on growing, buying, or organizing in your area, you can
reach the Sustainable Food Center at (512) 472-2073 or send email to <A
HREF="mailto:HN2953@handsnet.org">HN2953@handsnet.org</A>.

<P>

</FONT>

<FONT SIZE=1>
<CENTER>
