<HEAD>

<TITLE>Bioregionalism</TITLE>


</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<IMG SRC="images/folio.gif" ALT="GreenBeat!" ALIGN=top
WIDTH=456 HEIGHT=72><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<TABLE BORDER="0" WIDTH="456">
<TD>

<FONT SIZE=+3><CENTER>Of Place and People: Bioregionalism</CENTER></FONT>

<P>
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+1>by <STRONG>Marshall Frech</STRONG><BR>
</CENTER>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=+1>
Do you know where your drinking water comes from?  How about your food?  Where do
they go...eventually?  If you can't answer these questions you're like many
people who care for the earth but don't always know where to start that caring. 

<P>

--Enter Bioregionalism, a philosophy or working concept that employs a heightened
awareness of the ecological needs of the naturally-defined area in which you
live.  Or to borrow the artful phrase, it is "a new terrain of consciousness." 
For example: we who are lucky enough to live in the geographic area known as
Austin, Texas, might acknowledge that we live in the Hill Country, the distinct
geographical area marked by the Balcones fault.  This area has its own particular
environmental challenges such as delicate limestone aquifers, endangered species,
etc, plus myriad human factors such as forecasts for significant population
growth.

<P>

Actualizing the bioregional mindset changes the resource game a bit, there's a
different map, and some new ground rules.  The goal is to maintain the most
ecological stability that your community can muster within its local geography. 
Again, this agenda stems from the belief that the instructions on how to survive
in a particular region lie within its locally-attuned culture.

<P>

"After they grasp the basics, many environmentalists begin to think of themselves
as bioregionalists" says Ted Norris a local bioregional practitioner.  "And when
you consider," adds Norris, "that the average calorie in this country now travels
2000 miles before it is eaten, and that the U. S. is becoming more dependent on
other countries for food, a bioregional approach may yield ffers a few dearly
needed solutions."

<P>

In his book, Dwellers on the Land, author Kirkpatrick Sale applauds the
bioregionalist concept as an environmental effort "on a scale at which human
potential can match ecological reality."  This phrase smacks of down-to-earth
pragmatism and sensibility, but since the concept counters the great American
consumer mindset, applied bioregionalism turns out to be somewhat radical in its
implications.

<P>

For starters there are some just crazy, nutso, wacked-out things you can do
around your home like xeriscape your yard with native plants, support local food
growers (and retailers), and even trap rainfall from your roof into an old barrel
to irrigate your shade trees. There are an earthful of other activities to chose
from and people can apply themselves where-ever they see fit: cultural
restoration, neighborhood gardening, education, political activism, etc.

<P>

Perhaps bioregionalism's great asset is that its simple, local, hands-on nature
directs awareness back to the land.  In case you haven't noticed yet, the
environmental movement is getting more amorphous as it grows.  And with the
seduction of media crises drawing public attention away from core concerns, our
high-tech culture is increasingly deficient in regional knowledge.  The American
mind still leans precariously toward a global monoculture with all of its
postmodern conveniences.  We like to play golf in the desert, feast on
well-traveled calories, and entertain delusions of fail-safe developments in
fragile watersheds.

<P>

Bioregionalism isn't perfect, and it is not an all inclusive solution to
environmental problems.  But, there is a world of sustainability that needs
exploration and bioregionalism appears to be a map with a starting point.

<P>

* By the way, most of Austin's food is imported from California.  Our drinking
water comes from the local Colorado River, and our wastewater, after extensive
treatment, returns there. 

<P>

</FONT>

<FONT SIZE=1>
<CENTER>
