<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>What is a Bioregion?</TITLE>


</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<IMG SRC="images/folio.gif" ALT="GreenBeat!" ALIGN=top
WIDTH=456 HEIGHT=72><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<TABLE BORDER="0" WIDTH="456">
<TD>

<FONT SIZE=+3><CENTER>The Environmental Science of Bioregions</CENTER></FONT>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=+1>

<IMG SRC="images/bigbend.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALT="Big Bend" WIDTH=141 HEIGHT=290
BORDER=2>

The defining characteristics of a bioregion (much like an ecosystem) are usually
based on a variety of common physical characteristics including climate, soil,
landforms, microclimates, plant and animal communities, watersheds, and the human
cultures that exist there.

<P>

The scientific community has attempted to specify global bioregions through the
relationship of climate and natural vegetation;  These range from temperate
deciduous forest to temperate grassland, desert, or tropical scrubforest.

<P>

On a more local scale, the highly diverse geography of Texas has had several
different bioregional classifications.  The Natural Heritage Policy Project in
1978, at a meeting in Winedale, Texas, classified Texas into eleven natural
regions and twenty seven subregions.  Another, developed by the U.S. Fish and
Wildlife Service in 1979, classifies the State into eight major natural regions
and thirty five subregions.

<P>

<IMG SRC="images/ttexas.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="Texas" WIDTH=35 HEIGHT=36>&nbsp; See
accompanying story on <A HREF="texasbio.html">Bioregions of Texas</A>.

<P>

Bioregional concepts are useful as a planning aid and management tool to help us
more effectively use natural resources and to look at human impacts on the
environment.  Knowledge about bioregions and their components can also help us to
decide what areas are best suited for what purposes.  For example, identifying
areas that are floodplains is a first step for designating building limitations. 
A bioregional view can also help us in deciding what areas to set aside as
natural preserves, parks and other similar designations that will protect natural
ecosystems.

<P>

Increasing our knowledge of the place we live and acting responsibly on that
knowledge is essential to our long term survival as a species.  Viewing the world
in terms of bioregions and ecosystems is a major step on the road to building a
cooperative sustainable relationship with our environment.

<P>

</FONT>

<FONT SIZE=1>
<CENTER>
