<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Eco-Location</TITLE>


</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<IMG SRC="images/folio.gif" ALT="GreenBeat!"
WIDTH=456 HEIGHT=72 ALIGN=top><BR>

<IMG SRC="images/compass.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALT="Compass" WIDTH=110 HEIGHT=113>

<FONT SIZE=+3>&nbsp;<BR>
Eco-Location: <BR>
Charting Sustainability</CENTER></FONT><BR CLEAR=ALL>

<FONT SIZE=+1>

Location awareness is synonymous to environmental awareness for bioregionalists.
A small nonprofit group in Austin, Texas is putting this concept to practical
purposes through a new and unique method: an Eco-Location Map.

<P>

The Hill Country Foundation recently published a colorful and highly detailed map
of the Austin-area illustrating the geologic and natural history of the region
through graphics and text. The map, worthy of wall-hanging, provides extensive
information about the "ecological lay of the land," noting environmentally
sensitive areas such as aquifer recharge zones, endangered species habitats,
proposed wildlife preserves and sensitive woodlands. A "preferred growth
corridor," located mainly along the city's eastern section which lies in the less
environmentally sensitive Blackland Prairie region, is also noted on the map.

<P>

Inexpensively priced at $3.50, the Foundation is marketing the map to citizens,
businesses and realtors to encourage environmentally-informed decisions when
buying or building a home or locating a business.

<P>

"Because Austin straddles the sensitive Edwards Aquifer and is home to more
listed endangered species than any urbanizing area in the country," says Helen
Ballew, Executive Director of the Hill Country Foundation, "Austin's growth must
be carefully managed so that its natural assets are not inadvertently
squandered."

<P>

By understanding the needs and limitations of the local environmental resources,
the Foundation hopes homeowners and businesses will avoid developing in the most
environmentally sensitive areas.

<P>

Helen says she hopes people use the eco-location map just as bats and whales use
echolocation to avoid obstacles in their path.

<P>

"Most people are concerned for the environment. We want to give them information
they otherwise wouldn't have and trust them to make good choices," she notes.

<P>

The Foundation has conducted workshops on how to use the eco-location map with
area realtor and business groups, as well as with contractors and construction
companies.

<P>

"For a long time it's been thought that what environmentalists do is against
business interests. Protecting the environment makes good economic sense to our
community in the long run."

<P>

The Foundation is currently fundraising to mount additional educational and
promotional initiatives for the eco-location map. In the future they would like
to develop eco-location maps for other cities in the Texas hill country,
including San Antonio. Additionally,  the Foundation is involved in conservation
and  land trust efforts for the hill country.

<P>

In Austin, the eco-location map is available at Whole Foods Markets, Book People,
Miller Blueprint, TravelFest, Venture Map & Globe, Eco-Wise, Barnes & Noble,
Whole Earth Provision Company, Austin Convention & Visitor's Bureau, and the
Eastside Community Farmers' Market.

<P>

For more information about the Hill Country Foundation or the eco-location map,
call 512-478-5743 or write to 1800 Guadalupe, Suite C, Austin, Texas 78701.

<P>

</FONT>

<FONT SIZE=1>
