<TITLE>GreenBeat! Sprockets</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<IMG SRC="images/folio.gif" ALT="GreenBeat!" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=456 
HEIGHT=72><BR>

<H2>Bioregionalism Definitions</H2>

<P>

<IMG SRC="images/drkgreenball.gif" ALIGN=LEFT><STRONG>BIOME</STRONG>. The plants,
animals, and other organisms that make up a distinct biological community in any
climatic region.
<P>
 

<IMG SRC="images/drkgreenball.gif" ALIGN=LEFT><STRONG>BIOREGION</STRONG>. A natural area
defined by climate, soil, landforms, microclimates, plant communities, watersheds,
native plants and animals, and other factors including the human cultures that
exist there. 
<P>

<IMG SRC="images/drkgreenball.gif" ALIGN=LEFT><STRONG>ECOSYSTEMS</STRONG>.
Communities or functioning entities where the different species of plants,
animals, and microorganisms interact with each other and their physical
environment, including rock, soil, water, the atmosphere, sunlight, and other
non-living components of the environment. 
<P>

<IMG SRC="images/drkgreenball.gif" ALIGN=LEFT><STRONG>MICROCLIMATE</STRONG>. The
climate of a very small area, such as the bottom of a canyon, a wooded area, or
an animal's burrow. 
<P>

<IMG SRC="images/drkgreenball.gif" ALIGN=LEFT><STRONG>PLANT COMMUNITIES</STRONG>.
Populations of plants inhabiting a common area and interacting with each other
and their environment.
 
<P>

<IMG SRC="images/drkgreenball.gif" ALIGN=LEFT><STRONG>SUSTAINABLE DEVELOPMENT</STRONG>. 
Forms of economic activity that do not destroy, deplete, or
degrade natural resources and the environment upon which present and future
societies depend.

<P>

<IMG SRC="images/drkgreenball.gif" ALIGN=LEFT><STRONG>SUSTAINABLE LIVING</STRONG>. 
Using potentially renewable resources in such a way, and at a
rate, so they can be replenished naturally, and not overloading the capacity of
the environment to cleanse, renew, and maintain itself by natural processes.

<P>

<IMG SRC="images/drkgreenball.gif" ALIGN=LEFT><STRONG>WATERSHED</STRONG>. The
area drained by a river system, stream or creek.

<P>

