<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>GreenBeat! Profile</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>



<IMG SRC="images/folio.gif" ALT="GreenBeat!" ALIGN=top WIDTH=456 HEIGHT=72><BR>
<P>

<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3>Profile: Pam&#233;la Overeynder</FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>Sustainable Living in Strawbale</FONT><P>

<FONT SIZE=+1>Story & Photos by Pamela Colloff</CENTER><BR>
<P>


<FONT SIZE=+3>T</FONT><FONT SIZE=+1>here are no gas stations or convenience stores on the long, lonely stretch of
Hays County Road outside of San Marcos, Texas. After the occasional pick-up truck
or grazing cow, it dead-ends. A few paces beyond the "No Outlet" sign at the
pavement's end lies an eager black dog and the entrance to Stonehaven Ranch,
where Pam&#233;la Overeynder, 48, lives and works. 
<P>
<IMG SRC="images/pamela.jpeg" ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=165 HEIGHT=157 HSPACE=5>
"At first, I thought it would be
lonely out here," says Pam&#233;la, "but I really enjoy my own company and the
silence." The ranch -- which serves as a retreat for non-profit groups -- has
several houses, a vegetable patch, a windchime garden, 170 acres of sparsely
wooded land, and lots of time to think. 
<P>


Pam&#233;la serves as a resource for people
who want to build straw bale homes in Texas. After working for Head Start in
Dallas for ten years and then attending art school in Boston, Pam&#233;la was awarded
a grant in the mid-1980s to research the life of Gertrude Duby,
an environmentalist photographer who fought for the preservation of the Lacandon rainforest. While researching Duby's life in Mexico for two years, she
says, "I discovered how deep and wide the environmental crisis was. <P>


"It wasn't until I moved to Mexico that I came to know in
depth of the water crisis, of the species extinction crisis, of the greenhouse
gases, of the deforestation, of global warming." Before this experience, Pam&#233;la
explains, she had spent more time debating which environmental cause to devote
herself to instead of simply taking action. "When I left Mexico in 1989, it was
very clear that all of those pieces were connected. It didn't really matter which
piece you worked on, because they were all connected. I knew it was a major
crisis and I was going to be involved in it one way or another...I became aware
that I needed to become proactive." 
<P>
It wasn't until 1992 when Pam&#233;la was working
for the Austin-based Foundation for a Compassionate Society -- a feminist foundation working for peace and justice -- that her work in the
nuclear freeze movement led her to learn the basics of straw bale building. The
foundation had decided to build a gathering place near a Nevada nuclear test site
on lands that would then be returned to its original owners, the Native Americans
of the Western Shoshone Nation. 
<P>
<IMG SRC="images/madre.jpeg" ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=288 HEIGHT=294>
"We did the project as a demonstration, showing a
useful, environmentally sane way to build with a low-cost building technology,"
says Pam&#233;la. "I wanted to demonstrate a renewable building material that was not
trashing the environment, and straw is an annually renewable resource. 
<P>
"We
figured if we could convert away from lumber and use straw, we would save a lot
of greenhouse gases," she continues. "In California, at the end of the year, they
burn the straw back. That's a ton of greenhouse gases. We figured that we could
not only take some of the pressure off of forests, but we would prevent a lot of
that burning." 

<P>
Another reason they chose to build with straw is because it is an
excellent insulation material. Since straw bales are solid masses measuring 18
inches wide, they are much thicker, cheaper, and more effective than traditional
insulating materials. So not only does straw bale building significantly cut the
costs of heating and cooling, but also the costs of actual construction; rather
than having to spend a great deal of money on professional construction workers
and contractors, almost anyone with some brief training in straw bale building
can participate in the process. 

<P>Pam&#233;la and several other participants in
the project learned the basic techniques of straw bale building in a workshop at
the Tucson, Arizona organization:  <STRONG>Out on Bale</STRONG>. Then, after a master carpenter
had assisted them in Nevada with laying the foundation of concrete mixed with fly
ash, Pam&#233;la and about ten other participants began to build.<P>

First, Pam&#233;la explained, they lay the bales of straw like bricks, pinned them together with
wooden dowels, and wrapped the bales in chicken wire. Then they applied the first
layer of stucco, which adhered to the chicken wire and dried into the straw. They
applied another layer of stucco, and then a final layer of stucco which was
pigmented a light brown desert tone. 
<A HREF="http://solstice.crest.org/efficiency/straw_insulation/eip/Bainbridge.html">
[For a photo essay on strawbale building see David Bainbridge's slides at Straw Bale Construction]</A><P>
 
"We camped by the site, which we made into a
home base," says Pam&#233;la of the women-led project. "People slept in tents and vans
and under the stars." The foundation was completed in two weeks, and the rest of
the structure was built almost entirely by women in a little over a month. It
currently serves as a place for travelers and nuclear activists to pause and
reflect as well as learn from the caretaker about its construction. 
<P>
Not only does
straw bale building allow people to build their own homes, but it does not
necessitate spending much money -- approximately $20 per square foot. "You can do it
cheaper if you don't hire any of the labor, if you salvage materials, and you
don't pay for architects' plans," says Pam&#233;la. "I've heard of people building
them for $8 to $10 [per square foot]. Convential housing is probably $65 a square
foot, although you can build for less or more." Since heating, cooling, and
maintenence costs are cut at least in half in a straw bale structure, it also
saves money in the long run. 
<P>
Many people are wary of building with straw because
they think it is highly flammable. However, Pam&#233;la explains that fire is not a
concern since straw bales are packed so tightly. As an example, she cites a
structure with a wood roof that had not yet been stuccoed; "Someone torched it
and the roof burned straight to the ground, but the straw bales just got a little
charred on the outside. [Straw bales are] so compacted. You have to have oxygen
to get a good burn." The greatest dangers, if straw is not plastered properly,
are insects and moisture. But, she adds, "if you do it correctly, it literally
doesn't disintegrate. And it's earthquake resistant." 

<P>
Pam&#233;la's work in Nevada
gave her the knowledge and experience to serve as a straw bale resource in Texas.
Many people find her listed in Out On Bale's newsletter, <I>The Last Straw</I>. She
tells people where they can obtain straw, other environmentally friendly building
materials, and blueprints as well as the names of people in specific parts of the
state who are building with straw. 
<P>
While straw bale building may seem like a new
idea, Pam&#233;la points out that it is a traditional building method in some parts of
Europe and Russia. Straw bale building was also popular in Nebraska at the turn
of the century. "They didn't have trees, but they had lots of hay and grain," she
explains. "Every one of them is still inhabited and in good condition. The church
there in Arthur, Nebraska is made of straw and it's a pretty big structure. So it
has a long lifetime and very little maintenance." 
<P>
For Pam&#233;la, straw bale building
is part of a larger idea about how to help the environment. "The idea is that we
get our needs met locally, rather than importing resources and materials from
around the world, because it's very energy consuming," she explains. "There's a
thing called Odom's law, which means that the waste products for one process
are the fuel products for another process; it's about keeping a closed system so
that you don't lose your wealth. You have a closed loop. There's no leakage,
there's no waste. That's an important way for us to learn to live sustainably."

<P>
For several years, Pam&#233;la has been saving up money and drawing floor plans for
her own straw bale home. For the time being, however, she will continue to live
on Stonehaven Ranch, where she can spend her time off sitting in the windchime
garden decorated with small marble statues or cooking with tomatoes from her
vegetable patch. As <I>GreenBeat!</I> is preparing to go, Pam&#233;la is flipping a whole
wheat tortilla over the burner flame. She piles fresh avacado, cilantro pesto,
lemon juice, tomatoes and garlic on top of the tortilla. 
<P>
"If building materials
become so excessively expensive, if they become prohibitive - that's what it's
going to take for the mainstream to look for alternatives. Straw will be in the
wings waiting," she says. "It tickles me to think about an office building made
out of straw. If you built it out of that kind of organic material, you'd almost
have to change what you did inside. Anything is possible." 
<P>
</FONT>

<FONT SIZE=2>
<CENTER>
