<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>GreenBeat! Profile</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>



<IMG SRC="images/folio.gif" ALT="GreenBeat!" ALIGN=top WIDTH=456 HEIGHT=72><BR>
<P>

<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3>Profile: J.T. Irick</FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>Building Green Homes & Careers</FONT><P>

<FONT SIZE=+1>Story & Photos by Pamela Colloff</FONT><P>
<IMG SRC="images/jt.jpeg" ALIGN=MIDDLE WIDTH=331 HEIGHT=245></CENTER><BR>


<FONT SIZE=+3>J.T. </FONT><FONT SIZE=+1>Irick, 21, is pulling weeds on an unusually hot and humid day in October. Inside
the newly constructed, environmentally friendly home that he helped build on
Austin's East Side, the radio is turned up full blast. Iram Hernandez is pacing
the house with a hammer looking for unfinished odds and ends while Milton
Mitchell's sneakers dangle from the attic trap door as he installs insulation.
<P>
"There's no shade anywhere out here," says J.T., recalling when he, 19-year-old
Iram, 20-year-old Milton, and other volunteers helped lay the house's foundation
during several scorchingly hot weeks in June. 
<P>
Even though it's hard work, J.T. --
who has put an enormous amount of time, energy, and sweat into the house on
Walter Street -- is not complaining. He works seven days a week, both on this
project and at two other jobs, so that he can support himself and save up money
for college. He usually tries to go to bed early, since he must be at the site at
7:30, although he is rather sleepy this morning from having stayed up watching
the World Series. 
<P>
"I don't work on Sunday mornings," he says with a laugh,
explaining that when he calls friends then, they are usually asleep. "That's not
usually a time when people want to hang out!" 
<P>
The Walter Street house, which a
woman will move into the following weekend, is part of the Casa Verde Building
Program -- an attempt to put at-risk youth to work on environmentally friendly
homes for low income families and individuals. The program simultaneously
provides jobs and job training for drop-outs and juvenile criminals, allows
indigent families to own their own homes, rejuvenates disadvantaged
neighborhoods, and demonstrates environmentally friendly and efficent building
materials and techniques. 
<P>
"The first house we worked on took a while, but this
has gone much faster because we have the hang of things. Basically we know what
we need to do, how to do it, and how long it's going to take. Right
now, we're doing touch ups, getting rid of dents, vacuuming, puttying up -- we
call them 'boogers,'" J.T. says with a laugh. 
<P>
The Case Verde program is funded by the community
service organization AmeriCorps. After working 1700 hours on a Casa Verde project
for minimum wage (or $5 an hour for peer trainers like J.T.), workers are given
$4725 for college tuition. Regular paychecks and the discipline of working help
many at-risk youth get back on their feet. 
<P>
It was not very long ago that J.T.,
who just completed his first year in the Casa Verde program, had dropped out of
school and was working a dead-end job he hated. But after a year in the program,
he is not only highly experienced in green building construction and excited to 
learn more in college about the building process, but he is also extremely well-versed in 
environmentally friendly materials and building practices. 
<P>
"Our exterior walls are made of faswall, which is natural fibers that have been
compacted together. It has a very high R rating -- it's supposed to be really good
[for insulating]," he explains. "Our concrete that we use is 12 percent fly ash.
We use cedar trim on the outside of the house, because cedar is a much stronger
wood than pine; it lasts longer. We use metal studs instead of wood studs. We
don't use shingles, we use metal because it lasts longer. These walls
are made out of straw and hay, compacted, with electrical wires bored out in
them. These windows are double-paned windows, so it's harder for the heat or cold
to get inside. 
<P>
<IMG SRC="images/quote.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=338 HEIGHT=115>
"We're also working on putting solar screens on the houses to cut
the cost of electric bills," says J.T. "The first house that we built which used
all of these different materials has cut the bills in half." 
<P>
J.T. has worked on
this project side-by-side with high school drop-outs, former gang members,
juvenile criminals on probation, and teens from the Brownsville and Giddings
juvenile detention centers. For J.T., the experience working with other people
has been mixed. Although he has made close friends, sometimes he thinks it's
difficult to work collaboratively. 
<P>
"It can be frustrating at times," he says. "I
found out that not everybody likes to work the way I do. Some people like to take
five minute breaks after working for twenty minutes. I grew up in a small town,
small town atmosphere...I'd heard that things were different down here [in
Austin], -- the work ethic. It's been hard." 
<P>
The experience of building a house,
with all of its ups and downs, has made J.T. want to learn more about
construction and apply the techniques of green building to other structures. 
<P>
"I
haven't seen many houses that were built to be environmentally friendly," he
says. "I want to go into construction, maybe working for a corporation or a big
name architect." He hopes to study in a construction management program at Austin Community College, where "you learn how to read blueprints, work with
concrete and wood, lay a foundation." Once he's learned the basics, he can apply
what he's learned from the Casa Verde program. 
<P>
"Not every piece of wood that you
finish with is trash; just because you used it for a concrete form doesn't mean
you can't use it in the attic for a brace," he explains. "There are ways to build
houses that may be a little more expensive because of the material, but in 20 or
30 years, you will have saved money."
<P>
<CENTER><HR WIDTH=72></CENTER>
<P>
The following weekend, J.T. is standing in formal clothes outside of the house on
Walter Street. The lawn has been cleared of extra building materials, as has a
paint-spattered picnic bench. The house's new owner beams as people from the
surrounding neighborhood, city government, AmeriCorps, and the Casa Verde program
mill about the sunny 1300-square-foot home with large windows, a cathedral
ceiling, and a sprawling porch. 
<P>
Since the house was built relatively cheaply with
environmentally friendly materials, the house is extremely affordable. The new
owner put down a down payment of $1500 and must pay between $300 to $400 a month
for the zero-interest mortgage. Although the house is valued at around $65,000,
she will own the house once her payments total $40,000. Not only is the house
affordable, but the cost of upkeep will be minimal; Casa Verde estimates that the
house's utility bills will be half or less than half the bills of a comparably
sized house built with conventional building materials. 
<P>
With light bulbs flashing
and a sprinkling of applause, J.T. smiles, explains to the crowd how the house was
built to save energy and be environmentally friendly, and then presents the new
owner with her keys. "I really enjoy this," he says later, seeming relieved that
the project is completed and anticipating the house he will begin working on the
following week. "I feel like I'm really giving something back to the environment
and the community."
<P>
<P>
</FONT>

<FONT SIZE=2>
<CENTER>
