<HTML> <HEAD>

<TITLE>GreenBeat! Extra</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>



<IMG SRC="images/folio.gif" ALT="GreenBeat!"
ALIGN=top><BR> <P>

<IMG SRC="images/straw.jpeg" ALIGN=MIDDLE WIDTH=456 HEIGHT=69><BR>
<FONT SIZE=-1><P>
(Above image: a cross-section view of Stramit)</FONT><P>

<FONT SIZE=+3>S</FONT><FONT SIZE=+1>traw, once maligned by the three little pigs, is making a comeback as a viable
building material noted for its economy, aesthetics and
environmental-friendliness.<P>

An age-old building material, intact straw has been found in the ancient tombs of
Egyptian pharaohs, in the adobe of pre-Colombian dwellings and in the walls of
Nebraska farmhouses built a century ago. Whether used in making earthen bricks,
strawbale structures or even interior walls, today straw is proving itself
impenetrable to termites and temperature, wind and big bad wolves.<P>

In Perryton, Texas, in the high sweeping plains of the panhandle, a small
business is getting bigger everyday in the manufacturing and sales of compressed
straw walls called Stramit.<P>

"Our growth is due to the rising cost and unavailability of lumber and that
people are looking for environmental alternatives," explained Stramit USA chief
executive Cindy Thyfault.<P>

Straw is often confused with hay. Hay is dried grasses used mostly in the feeding
of livestock; while straw is the by-product left after the harvesting of cereal
grains like wheat, rice, rye and oats.<P>

"Unlike hay, straw itself is very inert and low in protein content. So there is
not protein breakdown in the (Stramit) panels," Thyfault said, debunking the myth
that straw walls easily deteriorate.<P>

According to Thyfault, in America alone more than 200 million tons of straw is
burned or plowed under every year. "With Stramit, this recycled waste produces a
usable and cost-effective material. No water, binder glues or fillers are used in
the production process either," she said.<P>

In the Stramit process, developed in Sweden and widely used in buildings in Great
Britain for more than 40 years, straw is tightly compressed and heated to 500&#176;F
with metal plates. Under this heat and compression, the straw emits its own
resin, bonding into a rigid and durable panel.  A high quality plaster finish on
the outside of the panels give Stramit a traditional interior wall appearance.<P>

Because the straw is compressed so densely, Stramit is extremely fire resistant
and ranks high marks in both thermal insulation and sound ratings.  "And our
customers see a 10-to-30% savings in material costs and a 20-to-50% labor cost
savings as compared with traditional construction materials and methods,"
Thyfault said. "Also, if the time ever comes for demolition, Stramit panels are
totally biodegradable," she added.<P>

Stramit USA recently received a $500,000 grant from the US Department of
Agriculture to continue researching and developing building materials made from
straw, including other wall partition systems and exterior load-bearing walls.
"We're developing value-added products," noted Thyfault.<P>

In the next two years, Thyfault projects tripling her production work crew and
adding another Stramit-process machine to her assembly operations.<P>

While straw was once considered an agricultural waste residue, it now brings
additional revenues to farmers and rural communities like Perryton, Texas. As an annually renewable crop, straw is a perfect
greenbuilding material: inexpensive, energy-efficient, and completely
sustainable.<BR>



<BR CLEAR=ALL>
</FONT>

