<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Career Q&A</TITLE>


</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<IMG SRC="images/folio.gif" ALT="GreenBeat!" 
WIDTH=456 HEIGHT=72 ALIGN=top><BR>

<TABLE WIDTH=456>
<TD COLSTART=1>

<IMG SRC="images/carrie.jpeg" ALIGN=MIDDLE WIDTH=144 HEIGHT=177><BR>
</TD>
<TD COLSTART=2 ALIGN=CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+2>
<STRONG>A Sustainable Education</STRONG><P>
</FONT>

<FONT SIZE=+1>

by <STRONG>Carrie Strahan</STRONG><P>
Graduate Student, University of Texas at Austin School of
Architecture<P>

Intern, Green Builder Program - City of Austin Environmental and
Conservation Services Department<P>

</TD>

</TABLE>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1>

I decided to go back to school and study architecture for two main reasons:
	
	<UL>
	<LI>because of my love of architecture - its eloquent way of blending technology and
	art in a three dimensional form,  <P><LI>and because I was dissatisfied with the current
	building practices.  </UL>
	
I was witnessing a lack of consideration for how the built
environment affected and responded to the natural environment.  Buildings were
going up left and right that did not take into account matters such as solar
access, natural lighting, or material toxicity.  Builders, architects, and
planners do not realize the long term impact their local decisions have on the
earth's natural resources.  A profound concern for the relationship between the
natural and built environment is a underlying philosophy in the profession known
as green building.
<P>
In my search for a college that emphasized green building design and
technologies, I found three schools that offered courses associated with the
green building industry.  They were the University of California at San Diego
(UCSD), Arizona State University (ASU), and the University of Texas at Austin
(UT).  The year I applied to UC San Diego the program was shut down because of
California budget cuts.  Arizona State University only accepted students with an
undergraduate degree in architecture (which I did not have, my undergraduate
degree is in engineering).  This left me with one choice, the University of Texas
at Austin.
<P>
My experience while attending (and still attending) UT is filled with mixed
emotions.  While I enjoy the variety of courses, high level of expertise, and
technical  resources, I find it difficult to find up to date information related
to green building.  And let's face it, there just aren't that many students and
faculty interested in green building issues.  One professor, Michael Garrison,
does concentrate many of his efforts on green building.  He offers a course
called "Sustainable Architecture" which is an introduction to the principles of
green building.  The course includes a series of lectures from builders,
architects, policy makers, and planners who are actively involved in green
building issues.  Last fall, Professor Garrison devoted an entire studio to
designing a sustainable village using a prescribed set of green building
principles.  The assignment was an actual project in Big Bend National Park in
southwest Texas to house Park employees and many of the students' ideas were
adopted into the Master Plan.  The project began construction last October. 
There are other examples of architecture courses that touch upon environmentally
sensitive issues, but as an overall design philosophy, green building design
takes a back seat to other issues.  And, while it is recognized that the intent
of a graduate program in architecture is to introduce the student to a variety of
options, it also seems pertinent to keep up with current concerns.  Because of
the growing amount of environmental degradation from bad building practices,
concern for the physical environment and discussion of architectural solutions
warrants significant attention.
<P>
To further my knowledge of green building issues, I realized I had to go beyond
the walls of University.  Fortunately, Austin has a wide variety of learning
environments in terms of green building options.  First, there is the Sustainable
Building Coalition, a local non-profit organization comprised of architects,
builders, homeowners, and others that are interested in sharing their knowledge. 
Monthly meetings feature a lecture series with topics such as Healthy Home
Design, Photovoltaics, and Alternative Wastewater Systems, to name a few. 
Secondly, The City of Austin Environmental and Conservation Services Department
has a Green Builder Program.  This program is recognized worldwide for their
commitment to encouraging resource conservation, reducing resource usage, and
promoting energy efficiency.  These two programs offer high level of hands-on
experience and expertise and have greatly enhanced my knowledge of green building
issues.
<P>
Now some may ask, why get a formal degree when most of the information is "out
there", in the real world?  Good question.  It is because a formal education
offers benefits that cannot be found "out there".  It offers a historical and
theoretical perspective that can shed light into the how and why buildings are
built, and discloses where the roots of green architecture originate.  Green
building roots can be found in many other types of building philosophies: in
indigenous architecture's use of local materials; in the visions behind some of
Frank Lloyd Wright's work and his reference to nature, and even in some aspects
of Modernism.  In short, it serves as a foundation on which to build upon.  It is
like taking a ballet class and learning the proper techniques before trying a
modern dance class; one must learn the basic movements and positions before
diverging from them.
<P>
Green building is a burgeoning line of architecture and the academic environment
cannot keep up with the pace.  Networking, meeting people, attending workshops,
taking classes, and hands-on experience are all needed to keep up with the
current green building technologies.  A formal education combined with hands-on
experience complement each other in a way that better prepares me for my future. 
As in any new, fast growing field of study, it is wise to keep abreast of all
kinds of information in whatever way it becomes available.<P>

<HR>

For additional information on pathways to environmental education and careers, see:<P> 

<A HREF="http://www.eco.org/">The Environmental Careers Organization</A><BR>
<A HREF="http://www.cs.cmu.edu/afs/cs/user/mkant/Public/FinAid/finaid.html%0D">
College Financial Aid Information</A><BR>
<A HREF="http://www.execpc.com/~insider/electron.html">College Grad Job Hunter</A><BR>
<A HREF="http://www.occ.com/occ">Online Career Center</A><P>

The Internet email list ENVJOBS-L - The Environmental Jobs List - provides postings about 
employment opportunities in the environmental sector. To subscribe to the ENVJOBS-L:<BR>
<OL>
	<LI> address an email message to listproc@pan.cedar.univie.ac.at
	<LI> leave the subject line blank
	<LI> in the body of the message type<BR>
	<CENTER>subscribe ENVJOBS-L "yourfirstname yourlastname"</CENTER><BR>
</OL>
<HR>

</FONT>



