<HEAD>

<TITLE>GreenBeat! Sprockets</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<IMG SRC="images/folio.gif" ALT="GreenBeat!" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=456 
HEIGHT=72><BR>

<H2>Green Building Definitions</H2>

<P>
<CENTER>edited by Wendy Todd</CENTER><P>

<IMG SRC="images/drkgreenball.gif" ALIGN=LEFT><STRONG>ALTERNATIVES</STRONG>. The evaluation of other construction methods and building materials
that employ natural materials and ecological processes such as straw bale and
rammed earth. 
<P>

<IMG SRC="images/drkgreenball.gif" ALIGN=LEFT><STRONG>AUDIT</STRONG>. The monitoring of water usage or energy consumption. A public
utility should provide the information required to develop a usage or consumption
budget and to perform an audit. 
<P>

<IMG SRC="images/drkgreenball.gif" ALIGN=LEFT><STRONG>CERTIFIED SUSTAINABLY MANAGED</STRONG>. A designation for
wood that is harvested from a forest that exhibits similar ecological
characteristics of a natural forest with its balanced diversity of tree species and
wildlife habitat. 
<P>

<IMG SRC="images/drkgreenball.gif" ALIGN=LEFT><STRONG>COMPOST</STRONG>. Fertilizer that is the byproduct of decomposed organic
waste, food and plant material. 
<P>

<IMG SRC="images/drkgreenball.gif" ALIGN=LEFT><STRONG>DAYLIGHTING</STRONG>. The utilization of natural light to
minimize the need for artificial illumination during the day.
<P>

<IMG SRC="images/drkgreenball.gif" ALIGN=LEFT><STRONG>EFFICIENT FIXTURES
AND APPLIANCES</STRONG>. Fixtures and appliances that function as their conventional
counterparts perform better by decreasing the use of water and/or energy - 
low flow faucets, showerheads, and toilets save water and energy efficient
appliances use less electricity.
<P>
 
<IMG SRC="images/drkgreenball.gif" ALIGN=LEFT><STRONG>ENERGY OR WATER CONSERVATION</STRONG>. Using less energy or
water, which can be achieved by wearing more layers of clothing and lowering your thermostat
setting in winter months and by taking shorter showers and installing a shower
flow restrictor. 
<P>

<IMG SRC="images/drkgreenball.gif" ALIGN=LEFT><STRONG>EMBODIED ENERGY</STRONG>. The amount of energy required to bring a material
into its usable state.
<P> 

<IMG SRC="images/drkgreenball.gif" ALIGN=LEFT><STRONG>GREYWATER</STRONG>. Water that has been used for showering, clothes
washing, and other faucet uses (excluding the kitchen sink and toilet which are
referred to as <STRONG>BLACK WATER</STRONG>) that has re-use potential for landscape 
irrigation.
<P>

<IMG SRC="images/drkgreenball.gif" ALIGN=LEFT><STRONG>HABITAT</STRONG>. Preserving or re-creating a viable environment for all living 
things. 
<P>

<IMG SRC="images/drkgreenball.gif" ALIGN=LEFT><STRONG>LIFE
CYCLE ASSESSMENT</STRONG>. An analysis which evaluates the environmental burdens derived
from a product's extraction, processing, manufacture, transport, use and
maintenance, and disposal or re-use.
<P>

<IMG SRC="images/drkgreenball.gif" ALIGN=LEFT><STRONG>PASSIVE SOLAR DESIGN</STRONG>. Building design and
placement that permits natural processes such as radiation, convection,
absorption, and conduction to temper and ventilate the interior climate without
reliance on conventional heating, air conditioning, and other mechanical
equipment. 
<P>

<IMG SRC="images/drkgreenball.gif" ALIGN=LEFT><STRONG>PHOTOVOLTAICS (PV)</STRONG>. Solid state cells that convert sunlight into
electricity which can be used immediately, stored in batteries, or sold to a
utility. 
<P>

<IMG SRC="images/drkgreenball.gif" ALIGN=LEFT><STRONG>R-VALUE</STRONG>. The unit of thermal resistance used for comparing the insulating
values of different materials.  the higher the number, the greater the insulating
characteristics.  Its inverse is <STRONG>U-VALUE</STRONG> which is the rate of thermal 
absorption.
<P>


<IMG SRC="images/drkgreenball.gif" ALIGN=LEFT><STRONG>RAINWATER HARVESTING</STRONG>. Rain that falls on a roof or yard that is collected and held
in a storage tank (cistern) for household and/or garden use as a water supply
alternative or supplement to well drilling or municipal hook-up. 
<P>

<IMG SRC="images/drkgreenball.gif" ALIGN=LEFT><STRONG>RENEWABLE
RESOURCES</STRONG>. Commodities that are created or produced as fast as they are consumed. 
natural resources are not destroyed in the process. Examples include alternative
energy sources such as the hydro, wind, and solar power that will not be depleted so
long as rivers flow, the wind blows, and the sun shines. 
<P>

<IMG SRC="images/drkgreenball.gif" ALIGN=LEFT><STRONG>TOTAL COST ACCOUNTING</STRONG>.
The total cost, not simply the purchase price, as well as the environmental
impacts are assessed. 
<P>

<IMG SRC="images/drkgreenball.gif" ALIGN=LEFT><STRONG>VOLATILE ORGANIC COMPOUNDS (VOC)</STRONG>. Compounds that are
frequently found in many common building materials and household products which
contain chemicals that vaporize at room temperature and pressure. 
<P>

<IMG SRC="images/drkgreenball.gif" ALIGN=LEFT><STRONG>XERISCAPE</STRONG>.
Landscaping with drought tolerant or drought resistant plants that conserve water
and decrease maintenance.
<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>
