<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>GreenBeat! Profile</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>



<IMG SRC="images/folio1.gif" ALT="GreenBeat!" ALIGN=top WIDTH=456 HEIGHT=72><BR>
<P>

<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3>Profile: Tamara Saltman</FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+1>Bringing Water Quality Monitoring to Diverse Communities<BR>
and Building a Career in Environmental Sciences</FONT></CENTER><BR>
<P>
<IMG SRC="images/mug.jpeg" ALIGN=LEFT ALT="Tamara" HSPACE=10 WIDTH=89 HEIGHT=88>


<STRONG>Age:</STRONG> 20<BR>
<STRONG>Hometown:</STRONG> Austin, Texas<BR>
<STRONG>Education:</STRONG> Senior, Cornell University<BR>
<STRONG>Environmental Field:</STRONG> Natural Resources Ecology<BR>

<STRONG>Current Endeavor:</STRONG> Mohawk Native American Environmental Taskforce<BR>
<A HREF="career.html"><IMG SRC="images/career.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT
WIDTH=144 HEIGHT=18></A> 
<P>

<FONT SIZE=+3>T</FONT><FONT SIZE=+1>amara Saltman is poring over her
environmental law books when Greenbeat catches up with her in Ithaca, New York. 
Although it's only a few weeks into her senior year at Cornell University, Tamara
already has her work cut out for her.  In addition to earning a Bachelor of
Science Degree from the university's Natural Resources Ecology program, she is
leading an effort to improve water quality for the Mohawk Native American tribe
in upstate New York.

<P>"It wasn't your average summervacation," Tamara says modestly.  A native of 
Austin, Texas, Tamara's most recent environmental challenge has been developing
a water quality monitoring program with the Mohawks' Environmental
Taskforce. 

<IMG SRC="images/tamara1.jpeg" ALT="Tamara Saltman" ALIGN=RIGHT
HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 WIDTH=158 HEIGHT=270>

<P>According to Tamara, the Mohawks' water quality problems
began back in 1959 with the completion of the St. Lawrence Seaway. 
"There are four rivers that come together in this area [where] the
Mohawks have hunted and fished for ages," she says, explaining that the
Seaway's hydropower capabilities brought industry into the area.  "There
are a number of industrial plants around the reservation which have
polluted the river sediment with heavy metal contamination and PCBs."


<P>Tamara teamed up with Cornell chemistry Professor Steve Penningroth
this summer to advance the tribe's water monitoring program.  The
Mohawks have previously tested their water by shipping samples out to a
lab, but "now we're putting the tools in the hands of the community,"
says Tamara. 

<P>Water monitoring is just one function of the tribe's
Environmental Taskforce. This summer, the Taskforce tested mothers'
breast milk for toxins which can be accumulated by eating the local
fish.  Test results show that industrial contamination has taken its
toll; the breast milk of women living on one of the reservation's
islands shows higher levels of PCBs than the breast milk of women in
other parts of the state.  In response to such dangers, the tribe is
developing an aquaculture project designed to raise fish in cages up
off the river bottom so they do not contact the contaminated sediment.<P>

<IMG SRC="images/wes.jpeg" ALT="Wes Halverson" ALIGN=LEFT
HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 WIDTH=234 HEIGHT=194>

Tamara has been involved with water-based environmental issues since
she was in high school in Austin, Texas.  She cites her mentor and
friend Dr. Wes Halverson, an environmental science teacher then working
at the LBJ Science Academy, as one of the reasons she is now working to
protect the environment.  "Wes was really involved in environmental
work.  I worked closely with him and drew a lot of inspiration to work
in the field of water quality.  It was something that I could really
devote myself to."


<P>Through Wes' guidance, Tamara became involved with
the Colorado River Watch Network, a group of student and citizen
volunteers who test water quality along the Colorado River from north
central Texas to the Gulf.  "River Watchers aren't just science nerds,"
notes Tamara.  "They are directly involved in making Texas a better
place to live." 


<P>Armed with water quality data, Tamara and other LBJ
High School students lobbied the Austin City Council for a stronger
water quality ordinance.  Dr. Halverson remembers how Tamara - who was
not an experienced public speaker - quietly presented a convincing and
well researched argument to the council. The students were successful
with their message and the council responded with a ban on
phosphate-based detergents in the City. <P>

<IMG SRC="images/reillylrs.jpeg" ALIGN=LEFT ALT="EPA's Reilly" HSPACE=8 VSPACE=8
WIDTH=166 HEIGHT=259>

This accomplishment drew the
attention of the former head of the EPA, William Reilly, who visited
the program in 1991.  "I remember sitting up all night, going over and
over what we were going to say," says Tamara.  "I remember being very
nervous the next day before the presentation but once we started
talking, and explaining all the work we had done, I found I was able to
relax.  Afterwards, when the meeting broke up, we walked down to the
river and I got to talk to Mr. Reilly much more informally.  That was
really wonderful." 

<P>During Christmas break of her freshman year at
Cornell, Tamara tested her skills again.  The River Watch needed
someone to write a grant proposal to the United States Information
Agency (U.S.I.A.) for an exchange program with Russia.  "The people who
normally write the grant proposals were busy with other projects, so I
said I'll do it! and I started writing." 

<P>A few months later, Tamara -
who was only 18 when she wrote the proposal for $59,0000 - found out
that it had been accepted.  These funds sponsored the exchange progam
which began in the summer of 1994; 15 Austin River Watchers journeyed
to Russia for a raft trip down the Volga River.  In the process, they
learned about the ecology of the Volga and exchanged information on
their water quality monitoring procedures with their Russian
counterparts.  This past summer, <A HREF="extra.html">
15 Russian students came to Texas</A> and
learned about our water monitoring techniques while canoeing the
Colorado River. <P>

<IMG SRC="images/quote.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT ALT="Quote" HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10
WIDTH=215 HEIGHT=74>

<P>"I think the river trips helped sell the proposal, "
says Tamara.  "We really wanted these students to get to know and even
depend on each other, instead of just shaking hands. That really caught
the eye of the U.S.I.A.  That experience made me a lot more confident. 
I thought if I could write that grant on my Christmas vacation, then I
could do a lot of other things." 

<P>Her skill and determination has paid
off.  Last semester Tamara was hired by Cornell University to write the
management plan for the Arnot Forest, a piece of land donated to
Cornell's Department of Natural Resources at the turn of the century. 
The land - which includes a camp, a stream, and acres of forest - has
been underutilized by Cornell students and staff.  The Department was
trying to find ways to increase use of the property or sell it. 
	"What I found is that most people didn't even know it existed," says
Tamara.  "My recommendation was that with relatively little money the
Department could publicize the camp and let people know what it had to
offer.  This way they could generate a fund for improvements to the
campground." 

<P>After graduating, Tamara plans to study either water
resources or aquatic ecology in graduate school.  "I've had times where
I haven't known exactly what it is that I want to do. Lots of times!"
she says, laughing. "But as far as being involved in the environmental
movement as a whole, I don't have any doubts."<P>
</FONT>

