<HEAD>

<TITLE>Career Q&A</TITLE>


</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<IMG SRC="images/folio1.gif" ALT="GreenBeat!" 
WIDTH=456 HEIGHT=72 ALIGN=top><BR>

<TABLE WIDTH=456>
<TD>
<FONT SIZE=+2>


<CENTER>
<STRONG>Career Q&A with Tamara Saltman</STRONG><P>
</CENTER>

</FONT>

<FONT SIZE=+1>

<STRONG>GreenBeat!</STRONG>: Chart for us your path towards an environmental career...<P>

<STRONG>Tamara Saltman</STRONG>: In chronological order:<P>

<UL>
	<LI>High school environmental science class and participation in the Colorado River Watch Program (1989/1990 school year)
	<LI>Internship with the Lower Colorado River Authority (summer 1990)
	<LI>Internship with the Riverwatch Program (summer 1991)
	<LI>Internship with City of Austin Water Watchdog Program (summer 1992)
	<LI>Enrolled in Natural Resources Ecology program at Cornell University (fall 1992 to present)
	<LI>Riverwatch Foundation - wrote grant for coordinating exchange program (summer 1993)
	<LI>Riverwatch Russian Exchange Program participant (summer 1994)
	<LI>Teaching water quality monitoring science to Mohawk Native American Tribe (summer 1995).
</UL>

<STRONG>GB!</STRONG>: What's your next step?<P>

<STRONG>TS</STRONG>:  I'll study either water resources or aquatic ecology in graduate school.<P>

<STRONG>GB!</STRONG>: What early experiences influenced your career interests?<P>

<STRONG>TS</STRONG>: Camping and canoeing all over the U.S. with my family. And the mentorship of my 
high school science teacher Dr. Wes Halverson.<P>

<STRONG>GB!</STRONG>: What's your <EM>dream</EM> environmental job?<P>

<STRONG>TS</STRONG>: To not have to have one, because there wouldn't be any more problems to solve.<P>

<STRONG>GB!</STRONG>: What do you consider the most urgent environmental problem?<P>

<STRONG>TS</STRONG>: The worst problem is a general lack of funding and education!<P>

<STRONG>GB!</STRONG>: When did you have your greatest doubts about your future career?<P>

<STRONG>TS</STRONG>: After doing RiverWatch for five or six months, I got really tired of going to the creek every day, 
knowing something was wrong, and not being able to do anything about it.<P>

<STRONG>GB!</STRONG>: When did you have your greatest sense of self-efficacy?<P>

<STRONG>TS</STRONG>: Watching someone I had personally trained to train other people for Austin's 
Youth RiverWatch program.<P>

<HR>


Other educational pathways toward careers impacting water quality include:
Environmental Resource Management programs, Geology, Geography, Biology, Chemistry, Environmental 
Engineering, Public Policy Studies programs, Ecology, Education...<P>

For additional information on environmental careers, see 

<A HREF="http://www.eco.org/">The Environmental Careers Organization</A>.
</FONT>
<P>
