<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Programs/Science</TITLE>


</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<IMG SRC="images/folio1.gif" ALT="GreenBeat!" ALIGN=top
WIDTH=456 HEIGHT=72><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<TABLE BORDER="0" WIDTH="456">
<TD>

<FONT SIZE=+3><CENTER>Water Quality Monitoring
<A HREF="science.html#programs>Programs</A><BR>and the <A HREF="#science">Science</A> Behind Them</CENTER><P>
</FONT>

<FONT SIZE=+2>
<A NAME="programs">Water Quality Monitoring Programs:</A>
</FONT><P>
<FONT SIZE=+1>
Student and citizen volunteer water quality monitoring programs are a hotbed for
science education, for gathering needed environmental data, and for developing
careers and contacts that lead to jobs!  Many progressive education programs
have realized that students learn science much better if they gather actual
environmental data in the field.  Our rapidly growing Internet is proving to be
an important tool for these programs to centralize and share water quality data
and related information.  For tens of thousands of students across the country,
these programs are the starting point for an environmental career.
<P>
<IMG SRC="images/watert.jpeg" HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT 
 WIDTH= 252 HEIGHT= 167 ALT="Students Testing Water">
In Texas for instance, students working with the Colorado River Watch Network
(CRWN) have been active for nearly a decade, measuring water quality along 660
river miles that make up the lower Colorado River. The Texas Watch program run
by the Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission (TNRCC) serves nearly
20,000 members with programs around the state.
<P>
Among the largest of the water monitoring groups is GREEN (the Global Rivers
Environmental Education Network) which began in the mid 1980's in the Great Lakes
region of the U.S.  Today, GREEN's membership extends to 125 countries and all 50
states.  While the most direct goal of GREEN is environmental education and data
gathering, this program sets an important precendent for global environmental
cooperation.
<P>

Similar to GREEN, but not limited to water quality, is the White House's Project
GLOBE (Global Learning and Observations to Benefit the Environment.),  the
program is taylored for the gradeschool level.  According to Vice President Al
Gore, one of GLOBE's chief supporters, "GLOBE students are young scientists, tens
of thousands strong, learning about Planet Earth and then teaching us."  GLOBE's
students are working with teachers and scientists to develop a coherent picture
of environmental systems and their accompanying challenges.
<P>

See GreenBeat's <A HREF="net.html">On the Net Department</A> for GREEN and GLOBE Internet sites.
<P>
</FONT>

<FONT SIZE=+2>
<A NAME="science">Water Quality Monitoring Science:</A>
</FONT><P>

<FONT SIZE=+1>

The study of water pollution is generally divided in two catagories: Point Source
Pollution and Non-Point Source Pollution:

<P>
<B>Point Source</B> pollution is contamination that is directly traceable to a source
such as a factory, a sewer pipe or an oil spill.  Because it is directly
traceable to a source, point source pollution is more easily controlled than
non-point source pollution.  It is also a problem more easily stopped through
strict regulation.

<P>
<B>Non-Point Source</B> (NPS) pollution, on the other hand, makes up the vast majority
of pollution and is more difficult to trace and therefore to treat. NPS 
pollution is the name given to the contaminated waters that runs off the land
after a rain.  It is the result of roadway runoff, overuse of pesticides and
fertilizers in agriculture and other chemicals used in daily life.  Non- point
source pollution is the residue of a society with cheap and ready access to
potential pollutants.  Non-point source pollution is  also the most serious
problem facing water quality around the country.  Unlike its counterpart, point
source pollution, which can be reduced through tougher legal standards, reduction
of non-point source pollution requires behavioral change.

<P>
<B>Water Quality Monitors sample streams for some of the following parameters:
</B>

<P>

<IMG SRC="images/inject.jpeg" WIDTH=252 HEIGHT=183 ALT="Testing Water" ALIGN=LEFT>
<B>Dissolved Oxygen (DO)</B>: is an essential element for the survival of aquatic plants
and animals. Oxygen enters water naturally though gradual absorption  or through
a wave/tumbling action which physically mixes both elements. In addition, the
photosynthesis of water-based plants also produces the oxygen needed to support a
stable and diverse ecosystem. 

<P>
While constant high readings of oxygen indicate a
healthy waterway, the introduction of large amounts of organic matter can bring
about rapid depletion of oxygen levels and lead to massive fish kills. This
phenomena is due to the chemical demands of organic decomposition.

<P>
<B>Fecal Coliform</B>: Fecal coliform are bacteria from the feces of warm-blooded
animals (including humans). By themselves, these bacteria do not cause illness or
disease but their presence in large numbers may indicate the presence of other
harmful organisms. Fecal coliform counts are often highest at flood stages when
untreated water may enter the waterway. Persons contacting water with high fecal
coliform counts may subject themselves to the dangers of the associated malevolent
organisms.

<P>
<B>pH</B>: The assigned pH value indicates whether a body of water is acidic, neutral,
or basic. Most organisms thrive in near neutral waters but the increase of
emissions from automobiles and industry  have threatened lake and stream habitat
with the consequences of acid rain.

<P>
<B>Biochemical Oxygen Demand (BOD)</B>: This measurement checks the amount of organic
matter in water and the quantity of oxygen it demands. Organic matter occurs
naturally from vegetation but greater concern is given to human induced organic
matter from industry and wastewater treatment plants.

<P>
<B>Temperature</B> plays a large role in the physical, biological and chemical
characteristics of a river. Changes in temperature can affect dissolved oxygen
levels, aquatic plant growth rates, and the metabolism and health of aquatic
organisms. Among other factors, the number of shade trees along a streambank can
be vital.


<P>
<B>Phosphorus</B> is a naturally occuring, organic element essential to the the life of
a stream. However, when high levels of inorganic phosphorus like laundry
detergents and fertilizers are introduced the results can devastate the oxygen
content and the life of the stream with excessive algal blooms.


<P>
<B>Nitrogen</B> is another element fundamental to the growth of plants and animals. If
nitrogen levels increase dramatically, for instance, the plants and
micro-organism life can explode and exhaust the oxygen support of the stream.


<P>
<B>Ammonia</B>: This is a product of natural decomposition, but high levels can indicate
sewage leaks.


<P>

<IMG SRC="images/net.jpeg" WIDTH=252 HEIGHT=190 ALT="Students Sample Water Solids with a Net" ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B>Turbidity</B>: Murky water holds suspended solids like clay, silt, and industrial
waste. These solids work against the life supporting qualities of a stream and
increase the water's ability to absorb heat. Furthermore, toxics (insecticides,
etc.) bind to these sediments and may be picked up in the food chain.


<P>
<B>Total Solids</B>: This is a cumulative measure of some of the above parameters and
more (salt, debris, etc.). This index offers an indication of the collective
quality of the water from an aquatic life perspective.


<P>
<B>Bioassessment</B>:  This is a study focused on the presence (or absence) of certain
bottom dwelling insect larvae and aquatic life. Bioassessment is vital in guaging
the overall quality of a stream since chemical monitoring may miss pollution
entering the stream on any given day.<P></FONT>


